00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:18.630
with the fields of
neuroscience, et cetera,

00:08:18.630 --> 00:08:22.932
what is the difference between
neurology and psychiatry?

00:08:22.932 --> 00:08:26.700
- Well, I'm married to a
neurologist and I am a psychiatrist

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:28.850
and we make fun of each
other all the time.

00:08:31.102 --> 00:08:33.840
A lot of neuroscientists and
a lot of brain clinicians

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:36.532
actually think these two
should be in the same field

00:08:36.532 --> 00:08:38.240
at some point in the future,

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:40.890
they were in the past,
they started together.

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:44.350
Psychiatry though, focuses on disorders

00:08:44.350 --> 00:08:47.690
where we can't see something
that's physically wrong,

00:08:47.690 --> 00:08:49.030
where we don't have a measurable,

00:08:49.030 --> 00:08:52.510
where there's no blood test
that makes the diagnosis,

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:54.977
there's no brain scan that
tells us this is schizophrenia,

00:08:54.977 --> 00:08:57.513
and this is depression
for an individual patient.

00:08:58.570 --> 00:09:02.150
And so psychiatry is much more mysterious,

00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:05.640
and the only tools we have are words.

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:08.820
Neurologists are fantastic physicians.

00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:12.180
They see the stroke on brain scans,

00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:15.620
they see the seizure and
the pre-seizure activity

00:09:15.620 --> 00:09:19.360
with an EEG, and they can measure

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:22.580
and treat based on those measureables.

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:24.940
In psychiatry, we have
a harder job, I think.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:29.140
We use words, we have
rating scales for symptoms,

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:31.940
we can measure depression and
autism with rating scales,

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:34.360
but those are words still.

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:37.190
And ultimately, that's what
psychiatry is built around.

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:42.190
It's an odd situation because
we've got the most complex,

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:44.253
beautiful, mysterious,

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:48.350
incredibly engineered
object in the universe,

00:09:48.350 --> 00:09:52.220
and yet all we have are
words to find our way in.

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:56.530
- So, do you find that if
a patient is very verbal or

00:09:56.530 --> 00:10:00.130
hyper-verbal, that you have an
easier time diagnosing them,

00:10:00.130 --> 00:10:03.680
as opposed to somebody who's
more quiet and reserved?

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:06.960
Or it's, I could imagine the
opposite might be true as well.

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:08.620
- Well, because we only have words,

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:10.810
you've put your finger on a key point.

00:10:10.810 --> 00:10:14.090
If they don't speak that much,
in principle, it's harder.

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:15.860
The lack of speech can be a symptom.

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:17.160
We can see that in depression,

00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:19.820
we can see that in the negative
symptoms of schizophrenia,

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:21.320
we can see that in autism.

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:25.220
Sometimes by itself, that is
a symptom, reduced speech,

00:10:25.220 --> 00:10:26.570
but ultimately you do need something.

00:10:26.570 --> 00:10:29.360
You need some words to help guide you

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:33.100
and in fact, there's challenges
that I can tell you about

00:10:33.100 --> 00:10:35.303
where patients with depression

00:10:35.303 --> 00:10:38.150
were so depressed, they can't speak.

00:10:38.150 --> 00:10:41.420
That makes it a bit of a challenge
to distinguish depression

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:43.670
from some of the other reasons
they might not be speaking.

00:10:43.670 --> 00:10:47.630
And this is sort of the art
and the science of psychiatry.

00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:50.970
- Do you find that there are patients

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:54.480
that have, well, let's call
them comorbidities or conditions

00:10:54.480 --> 00:10:58.070
where they would land in both
psychiatry and neurology,

00:10:58.070 --> 00:11:01.130
meaning there's damage to a
particular area of the brain

00:11:01.130 --> 00:11:02.490
and therefore they're depressed?

00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:06.100
And how do you tease that
out as a psychiatrist?

00:11:06.100 --> 00:11:08.180
- Yeah, this happens all the time.

00:11:08.180 --> 00:11:10.303
Parkinson's disease is a great example.

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:15.540
It can be debilitating in so many ways.

00:11:15.540 --> 00:11:17.980
People have trouble moving,
they have trouble walking,

00:11:17.980 --> 00:11:19.650
they have trouble swallowing,

00:11:19.650 --> 00:11:24.650
and they can have a
truly severe depression.

00:11:25.170 --> 00:11:26.990
And this is where you
might say, "Oh, well,

00:11:26.990 --> 00:11:30.450
they've got a life-threatening illness",

00:11:30.450 --> 00:11:32.390
but there are plenty of
neurological disorders

00:11:32.390 --> 00:11:37.390
where depression is not a
strongly comorbid symptom,

00:11:37.670 --> 00:11:40.050
like ALS, Lou Gehrig's
disease, for example,

00:11:40.050 --> 00:11:44.020
depression is not strongly
comorbid in that disease,

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:46.860
but in Parkinson's, it
is extremely common.

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:49.380
And as you know, in Parkinson's disease,

00:11:49.380 --> 00:11:53.400
we have loss of the dopamine
neurons in the midbrain.

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:58.040
And this is a very specific
population of cells

00:11:58.040 --> 00:12:00.450
that's dying, and probably that leads

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:03.670
to both the movement
disorder and the depression.

00:12:03.670 --> 00:12:05.190
There are many examples of that

00:12:05.190 --> 00:12:06.830
where these two fields come together

00:12:06.830 --> 00:12:09.270
and you really need to work as a team.

00:12:09.270 --> 00:12:13.130
I've had patients in my clinic,
that I treat the depression

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:14.610
associated with their Parkinson's,

00:12:14.610 --> 00:12:16.580
and a neurologist treats the movement

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:19.780
associated with the Parkinson's
and we work together.

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:22.210
- Do you think we will
ever have a blood test

00:12:22.210 --> 00:12:24.740
for depression or schizophrenia or autism?

00:12:24.740 --> 00:12:27.993
And would that be a good or a bad thing?

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:33.100
- I think ultimately there
will be quantitative tests.

00:12:33.100 --> 00:12:34.910
Already, efforts are being made

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:38.800
to look at certain rhythms in
the brain using external EEGs

00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:40.940
to look at brain waves effectively,

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:43.450
look at the ratios of certain frequencies

00:12:43.450 --> 00:12:45.080
to other frequencies,

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:47.510
and there's some progress
being made on that front.

00:12:47.510 --> 00:12:49.310
It's not as good as it could be.

00:12:49.310 --> 00:12:51.140
It doesn't really give you the confidence

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:54.240
for the individual patient
that you would like,

00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:56.440
but ultimately, what's
going on in the brain

00:12:56.440 --> 00:12:59.760
in psychiatric disease is physical,

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:02.700
and it's due to the
circuits and the connections

00:13:02.700 --> 00:13:05.460
and the projections in the
brain that are not working

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:07.970
as they would in a typical situation.

00:13:07.970 --> 00:13:12.340
And I do think we'll have those
measureables at some point.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:14.766
Now, is that good or bad?

00:13:14.766 --> 00:13:15.687
I think that will be good,

00:13:15.687 --> 00:13:19.380
and one of the challenges
we have with psychiatry

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:21.980
is it is an art as well as a science

00:13:21.980 --> 00:13:26.510
to elicit these symptoms in a precise way.

00:13:26.510 --> 00:13:29.370
It does take some time,
and it would be great

00:13:29.370 --> 00:13:31.910
if we could just do quick measurements.

00:13:31.910 --> 00:13:35.240
Could it be abused or misused?

00:13:35.240 --> 00:13:36.073
Certainly.

00:13:36.073 --> 00:13:38.430
But that's I think true,
for all of medicine.

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:40.370
- I want to know, and I'm
sure there are several,

00:13:40.370 --> 00:13:42.700
but what do you see as
the biggest challenge

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:47.463
facing psychiatry and the
treatment of mental illness today?

00:13:49.300 --> 00:13:52.330
- I think we're making progress

00:13:52.330 --> 00:13:53.970
on what the biggest challenge is,

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:56.300
which I think there's
still such a strong stigma

00:13:56.300 --> 00:13:57.680
for psychiatric disease

00:13:57.680 --> 00:14:01.420
that patients often don't come to us,

00:14:01.420 --> 00:14:06.420
and they feel that they
should be able to handle this

00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:07.533
on their own.

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:10.770
And that can slow treatment.

00:14:10.770 --> 00:14:13.720
It can lead to worsening symptoms.

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:14.610
We know, for example,

00:14:14.610 --> 00:14:17.910
patients who have
untreated anxiety issues.

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:20.430
If you go for a year or more

00:14:20.430 --> 00:14:22.690
with a serious untreated anxiety issue,

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:24.400
that can convert to depression.

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:28.770
You can add another problem
on top of the anxiety.

00:14:28.770 --> 00:14:31.210
And so it would be...

00:14:31.210 --> 00:14:32.730
Why do people not come for treatment?

00:14:32.730 --> 00:14:35.210
They feel like this is
something they should be able

00:14:35.210 --> 00:14:38.300
to master on their own, which can be true,

00:14:38.300 --> 00:14:43.230
but usually, some help is a good thing.

00:14:43.230 --> 00:14:45.710
- That raises a question
related to something

00:14:45.710 --> 00:14:48.400
I heard you say many
years ago at a lecture,

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:51.360
which was that, this
was a scientific lecture

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:54.810
and you said, "We don't
know how other people feel.

00:14:54.810 --> 00:14:57.648
Most of the time, we don't
even really know how we feel."

00:14:57.648 --> 00:14:58.481
- [chuckles] Yeah.

00:14:58.481 --> 00:15:00.290
- [Andrew] Maybe you could
elaborate on that a little bit

00:15:01.665 --> 00:15:06.665
and the dearth of ways that we
have to talk about feelings.

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:09.000
I mean, there's so many words.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:10.120
I don't know how many,

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:12.920
but I'm guessing they're more
than a dozen words to describe

00:15:12.920 --> 00:15:16.330
the state that I call sadness,
but as far as I understand,

00:15:16.330 --> 00:15:17.760
we don't have any way of comparing that

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:20.910
in a real objective sense.

00:15:20.910 --> 00:15:23.520
As a psychiatrist, when
your job is to use words

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:26.870
to diagnose, words of
the patient to diagnose,

00:15:26.870 --> 00:15:28.650
do you maneuver around that?

00:15:28.650 --> 00:15:30.240
And what is this landscape

00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:32.263
that we call feelings or emotions?

00:15:33.130 --> 00:15:35.453
- This is really interesting.

00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:40.240
Here there's a tension between
the words that we've built up

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:44.010
in the clinic that mean
something to the physicians,

00:15:44.010 --> 00:15:46.200
and then there's the
colloquial use of words

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:47.280
that may not be the same,

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:49.600
and so that's the first
level we have to sort out

00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:53.660
when someone says, "I'm depressed",

00:15:53.660 --> 00:15:56.340
what exactly do they mean by that?

00:15:56.340 --> 00:15:58.520
And that may be different
from what we're talking about

00:15:58.520 --> 00:15:59.500
in terms of depression.

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:02.920
So part of psychiatry is
to get beyond that word,

00:16:02.920 --> 00:16:05.425
and to get into how
they're actually feeling,

00:16:05.425 --> 00:16:09.850
get rid of the jargon and
get to real world examples

00:16:09.850 --> 00:16:11.000
of how they're feeling.

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:16.680
So, how much do you look
forward into the future?

00:16:16.680 --> 00:16:19.010
How much hope do you have?

00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:21.060
How much planning are
you doing for the future?

00:16:21.060 --> 00:16:24.270
So here now you're
getting into actual things

00:16:24.270 --> 00:16:26.270
you can talk about that are unambiguous.

00:16:26.270 --> 00:16:30.190
If someone says, "Yeah, I can't
even think about tomorrow.

00:16:30.190 --> 00:16:33.707
I don't see how I'm going
to get to tomorrow".

00:16:34.778 --> 00:16:36.950
That's a nice, precise
thing that you know,

00:16:36.950 --> 00:16:40.947
it's sad, it's tragic, but
also, that means something.

00:16:40.947 --> 00:16:42.240
And we know what that means.

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:45.060
That's the hopelessness
symptom of depression.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:46.900
And that is what I try to do

00:16:46.900 --> 00:16:48.140
when I do a psychiatric interview.

00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:49.810
I try to get past the jargon,

00:16:49.810 --> 00:16:52.010
and get to what's actually
happening in a patient's life

00:16:52.010 --> 00:16:53.410
and in their mind.

00:16:53.410 --> 00:16:55.287
But as you say, ultimately,

00:16:55.287 --> 00:16:57.810
[chuckles] and this shows up across...

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:00.970
I address this issue every day in my life,

00:17:00.970 --> 00:17:04.980
whether it's in the lab where
we're looking at animals,

00:17:04.980 --> 00:17:08.700
whether fish or mice or rats
and studying their behavior,

00:17:08.700 --> 00:17:12.230
or when I'm in a conversation
with just a friend

00:17:12.230 --> 00:17:15.810
or a colleague, or when
I'm talking to a patient,

00:17:15.810 --> 00:17:17.640
I never really know what's going on

00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:19.573
inside the mind of the other person.

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:23.950
I get some feedback, I get words,

00:17:23.950 --> 00:17:27.250
I get behaviors, I get actions,
but I never really know.

00:17:27.250 --> 00:17:29.720
And as you said at the very
beginning of the question,

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:32.500
often we don't even have
the words and the insight

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:34.990
to even understand what's
going on in our own mind.

00:17:34.990 --> 00:17:37.900
I think a lot of psychiatrists
are pretty introspective.

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:40.080
That's part of the reason
they end up in that specialty,

00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:44.210
and so, maybe we spend a little more time

00:17:44.210 --> 00:17:45.050
than the average person

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:46.660
thinking about what's going on within,

00:17:46.660 --> 00:17:49.480
but it doesn't mean we have the answers.

00:17:49.480 --> 00:17:53.640
- So in this area of trying to figure out

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:55.970
what's going on under
the hood through words,

00:17:55.970 --> 00:17:58.930
it sounds like certain words would relate

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:03.070
to this idea of anticipation and hope.

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:05.170
Is it fair to say that
that somehow relates

00:18:05.170 --> 00:18:06.930
to the dopamine system in the sense

00:18:06.930 --> 00:18:10.490
that dopamine is involved
in motivated behaviors?

00:18:10.490 --> 00:18:13.190
I mean, if I say for instance,

00:18:13.190 --> 00:18:15.970
and I won't ask you to
run a session with me here

00:18:15.970 --> 00:18:17.950
[chuckles] for free.
[Karl laughs]

00:18:17.950 --> 00:18:19.110
- We'll do that off camera.

00:18:19.110 --> 00:18:20.760
- [Andrew] Off camera. Right.

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:25.760
If I were to say, "I just
can't imagine tomorrow.

00:18:27.147 --> 00:18:28.920
I just can't do it."

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:31.140
So that's not an action-based,

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:34.730
that's purely based on
my internal narrative,

00:18:34.730 --> 00:18:37.280
but I could imagine things like, you know,

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:40.630
I have a terrible time
sleeping, I'm not hungry,

00:18:40.630 --> 00:18:43.510
I'm not eating, so statements
about physical actions,

00:18:43.510 --> 00:18:46.459
I'm guessing also have validity.

00:18:46.459 --> 00:18:47.292
- Absolutely.

00:18:47.292 --> 00:18:50.290
- And there are now ways to measure

00:18:50.290 --> 00:18:51.830
the accuracy of those statements.

00:18:51.830 --> 00:18:53.730
Like for instance, if
I gave you permission,

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:55.890
you could know if I slept last night,

00:18:55.890 --> 00:18:57.110
or whether or not I was just saying

00:18:57.110 --> 00:18:58.350
I had a poor night's sleep.

00:18:58.350 --> 00:18:59.470
- Yes. That's right.

00:18:59.470 --> 00:19:02.750
- So in moving forward through 2021

00:19:02.750 --> 00:19:05.730
and into the next 10 and
100 years of psychiatry,

00:19:05.730 --> 00:19:10.730
do you think that the body
reporting some of the actions

00:19:11.050 --> 00:19:14.290
of a human are going to become useful

00:19:14.290 --> 00:19:16.930
and mesh with the words in a way

00:19:16.930 --> 00:19:19.020
that's going to make your job easier?

00:19:19.020 --> 00:19:19.970
- I do think that's true.

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:22.590
And the two things you've
mentioned, eating and sleeping,

00:19:22.590 --> 00:19:25.340
those are additional criteria

00:19:25.340 --> 00:19:26.910
that we use to diagnose depression.

00:19:26.910 --> 00:19:29.280
These are the vegetative signs,
we call them of depression,

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:30.540
poor sleep, and poor eating.

00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:32.480
And if you have a baseline for somebody,

00:19:32.480 --> 00:19:34.060
that's the real challenge there.

00:19:34.060 --> 00:19:35.730
What's different in that person?

00:19:35.730 --> 00:19:37.760
Some people with
depressed, they sleep more.

00:19:37.760 --> 00:19:40.560
Some people who are
depressed, they sleep less.

00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:41.650
Some people who are depressed,

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:44.970
they're more physically agitated,
and they move around more.

00:19:44.970 --> 00:19:46.060
Some people who are depressed,

00:19:46.060 --> 00:19:48.190
they move less even while they're awake.

00:19:48.190 --> 00:19:49.270
And so you need...

00:19:49.270 --> 00:19:51.860
Here's the challenge is
that you can't just look

00:19:51.860 --> 00:19:53.230
at how they are now.

00:19:53.230 --> 00:19:57.320
You have to get a baseline,
and then see how it's changed.

00:19:57.320 --> 00:20:02.320
And that can be a challenge
that raises ethical issues,

00:20:02.535 --> 00:20:04.740
and how do you collect
that baseline information

00:20:04.740 --> 00:20:05.770
from someone healthy?

00:20:05.770 --> 00:20:08.610
I don't think that's
something we have solved.

00:20:08.610 --> 00:20:11.920
Of course, with phones and
accelerometers and phones,

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:12.980
you could in principle,

00:20:12.980 --> 00:20:15.970
collect a lot of baseline
information from people,

00:20:15.970 --> 00:20:18.130
but that would have to be treated

00:20:18.130 --> 00:20:21.550
very carefully for privacy reasons.

00:20:21.550 --> 00:20:24.623
- And in terms of measuring
one's own behavior,

00:20:24.623 --> 00:20:25.456
I've heard of work that's going on.

00:20:25.456 --> 00:20:30.456
Sam Golden up in the
University of Washington

00:20:30.460 --> 00:20:32.120
who works on aggression in animal models

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:34.640
was telling me that there's
some efforts that he's making,

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:36.590
and perhaps you're involved
in this work as well,

00:20:36.590 --> 00:20:41.200
I don't know, of devices
that would allow people

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:42.630
to detect, for instance,

00:20:42.630 --> 00:20:44.790
when they're veering
towards a depressive episode

00:20:44.790 --> 00:20:47.260
for themselves, that they
may choose or not choose

00:20:47.260 --> 00:20:48.850
to report that to their clinician,

00:20:48.850 --> 00:20:50.230
maybe they don't even have a clinician.

00:20:50.230 --> 00:20:53.410
Maybe this person that you
referred to at the beginning,

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:54.830
this person who doesn't feel comfortable

00:20:54.830 --> 00:20:55.930
coming to talk to you,

00:20:57.770 --> 00:21:00.120
maybe something is measuring
changes in the inflection

00:21:00.120 --> 00:21:02.130
of their voice, or the speed

00:21:02.130 --> 00:21:03.590
at which they get up from a chair.

00:21:03.590 --> 00:21:04.970
Do you think that those kind of metrics

00:21:04.970 --> 00:21:06.840
will eventually inform
somebody, "Hey, you know,

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:08.030
you're in trouble"?

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:10.980
This is getting to back to the statement

00:21:10.980 --> 00:21:13.070
that I heard you make and
it rung in my mind now,

00:21:13.070 --> 00:21:14.410
I think for more than a decade,

00:21:14.410 --> 00:21:17.020
which is, "Oftentimes, we
don't even know how we feel."

00:21:17.020 --> 00:21:17.853
- Yeah.

00:21:17.853 --> 00:21:19.080
You know, that I do like,

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:22.120
because that gives the
patient the agency to detect

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:25.190
what's going on, and even
separate from modern technology,

00:21:25.190 --> 00:21:27.410
this has been part of
the art of psychiatry

00:21:27.410 --> 00:21:29.080
is to help patients realize

00:21:29.080 --> 00:21:32.060
that sometimes other people observing them

00:21:32.060 --> 00:21:35.000
can give them the earliest
warning signs of depression.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.930
We see this very often in family.

00:21:37.930 --> 00:21:40.530
They'll notice when
the patient is changing

00:21:40.530 --> 00:21:42.070
before the patient does.

00:21:42.070 --> 00:21:43.910
And then there are things
the patient may notice,

00:21:43.910 --> 00:21:47.520
but not correctly ascribe
to the onset of depression.

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:48.840
And a classic example of that

00:21:48.840 --> 00:21:51.250
is what we call 'early morning awakening'.

00:21:51.250 --> 00:21:53.520
And this is something
that can happen very early

00:21:53.520 --> 00:21:55.270
as people start to slide into depression.

00:21:55.270 --> 00:21:57.800
They start to wake up earlier and earlier,

00:21:57.800 --> 00:21:59.860
just inexplicably, they're awake at-

00:21:59.860 --> 00:22:02.150
- This is like 2:00 AM, 3:00 AM awakening?

00:22:02.150 --> 00:22:02.983
- It could start...

00:22:02.983 --> 00:22:05.645
Yeah, it could start at
5:00 AM, could go to four,

00:22:05.645 --> 00:22:06.478
and three-
- And are unable

00:22:06.478 --> 00:22:07.311
to fall back asleep?

00:22:07.311 --> 00:22:08.890
- Unable to fall back asleep. Exactly.

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:12.420
And they may not know
what to do with that.

00:22:12.420 --> 00:22:14.130
It could just be, [chuckles]
from their perspective,

00:22:14.130 --> 00:22:15.870
it's just something that's happening.

00:22:15.870 --> 00:22:18.110
But if you put enough of
that information together,

00:22:18.110 --> 00:22:20.417
that could be a useful
warning sign for the patient

00:22:20.417 --> 00:22:22.046
and it could help them seek treatment.

00:22:22.046 --> 00:22:24.910
And I think that is something
that could be really valuable.

00:22:24.910 --> 00:22:25.950
- Interesting.

00:22:25.950 --> 00:22:30.950
So, in this framework of
needing words to self-report

00:22:31.940 --> 00:22:34.377
or machines to detect how we feel

00:22:34.377 --> 00:22:38.513
and maybe inform a psychiatrist
how a patient feels,

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:42.170
touch on some of the technologies

00:22:42.170 --> 00:22:44.120
that you've been involved in building,

00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:47.013
but as a way to march into that,

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:52.230
are there any very good treatments
for psychiatric disease?

00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:55.650
Meaning, are there currently
any pills, potions,

00:22:55.650 --> 00:23:00.110
forms of communication that
reliably work every time,

00:23:00.110 --> 00:23:01.570
or work in most patients?

00:23:01.570 --> 00:23:03.920
And could you give a couple
examples of great successes

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:05.420
of psychiatry if they exist?

00:23:05.420 --> 00:23:06.290
- Yes.

00:23:06.290 --> 00:23:07.430
Yeah, we are fortunate.

00:23:07.430 --> 00:23:09.400
And this [chuckles] coming
back to my, you know,

00:23:09.400 --> 00:23:12.850
the joking between my wife and myself

00:23:12.850 --> 00:23:15.330
in terms of neurology and psychiatry,

00:23:15.330 --> 00:23:18.670
we actually in psychiatry,
despite the depths

00:23:18.670 --> 00:23:21.100
of the mystery we struggled with,

00:23:21.100 --> 00:23:24.110
many of our treatments are actually...

00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:26.180
We may be doing better
than some other specialties

00:23:26.180 --> 00:23:29.000
in terms of actually
causing therapeutic benefit

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:30.030
for patients.

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:34.770
We do help patients, the
patients who suffer from...

00:23:34.770 --> 00:23:36.710
By the way, both
medications and talk therapy

00:23:36.710 --> 00:23:39.430
have been shown to be extremely
effective in many cases,

00:23:39.430 --> 00:23:42.670
for example, people with panic disorder,

00:23:42.670 --> 00:23:45.210
cognitive behavioral therapy,
just working with words,

00:23:45.210 --> 00:23:47.320
helping people identify the early signs

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:49.610
of when they're starting to
move toward a panic attack,

00:23:49.610 --> 00:23:52.110
what are the cognitions
that are happening?

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:54.200
You can train people to derail that,

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:57.540
and you can very potently
treat panic disorder that way.

00:23:57.540 --> 00:24:00.430
- How long does something
like that take on average?

00:24:00.430 --> 00:24:02.420
- For a motivated, insightful patient,

00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:06.983
you can have a very
cookbooky series of sessions,

00:24:06.983 --> 00:24:09.670
that's six to 12 sessions, or even less

00:24:09.670 --> 00:24:12.060
for someone who's very
insightful and motivated

00:24:12.060 --> 00:24:14.660
and it can have a very
powerful effect that quickly.

00:24:15.530 --> 00:24:17.530
And that's just with words,

00:24:17.530 --> 00:24:19.590
there are many psychiatric medications

00:24:19.590 --> 00:24:22.430
that are very effective for the conditions

00:24:22.430 --> 00:24:23.970
that they're treating.

00:24:23.970 --> 00:24:26.680
Anti-psychotic medications,
they have side effects,

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:27.970
but boy, do they work!

00:24:27.970 --> 00:24:31.300
They really can clear up
particularly the positive symptoms

00:24:31.300 --> 00:24:35.340
of schizophrenia for example,
the auditory hallucinations,

00:24:35.340 --> 00:24:39.170
the paranoia, people's lives
can be turned around by these-

00:24:39.170 --> 00:24:40.820
- We should clarify positive symptoms.

00:24:40.820 --> 00:24:43.810
You mean not positive in
the qualitative sense,

00:24:43.810 --> 00:24:45.430
you mean positive meaning
that the appearance

00:24:45.430 --> 00:24:46.650
of something abnormal.

00:24:46.650 --> 00:24:47.510
- Exactly. Yeah.

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:48.800
Thank you for that clarification.

00:24:48.800 --> 00:24:50.470
When we say positive symptoms,

00:24:50.470 --> 00:24:52.210
we do mean the addition of something

00:24:52.210 --> 00:24:53.130
that wasn't there before,

00:24:53.130 --> 00:24:55.080
like a hallucination or a paranoia,

00:24:55.080 --> 00:24:57.760
and that stands in contrast
to the negative symptoms

00:24:57.760 --> 00:24:59.450
where something is taken away,

00:24:59.450 --> 00:25:02.650
and these are patients who are withdrawn.

00:25:02.650 --> 00:25:05.250
They have what we call thought blocking.

00:25:05.250 --> 00:25:08.443
They can't even progress forward
in a sequence of thoughts.

00:25:09.350 --> 00:25:12.170
Both of those can be
part of schizophrenia,

00:25:12.170 --> 00:25:14.420
the hallucinations and the paranoia

00:25:14.420 --> 00:25:15.960
are more effectively treated right now,

00:25:15.960 --> 00:25:18.220
but they are effectively treated.

00:25:18.220 --> 00:25:21.420
And then, this is a frustrating,

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:23.950
and yet heartening aspect of psychiatry.

00:25:23.950 --> 00:25:27.256
There are treatments like
electroconvulsive therapy,

00:25:27.256 --> 00:25:31.150
where it's extremely
effective for depression.

00:25:31.150 --> 00:25:35.490
We have patients who
nothing else works for them,

00:25:35.490 --> 00:25:37.390
where they can't tolerate medications,

00:25:37.390 --> 00:25:40.810
and you can administer under a very safe,

00:25:40.810 --> 00:25:42.530
controlled condition,

00:25:42.530 --> 00:25:44.620
where the patient's body is not moving.

00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:46.590
They're put into a very safe situation

00:25:46.590 --> 00:25:48.650
where the body doesn't move or cease,

00:25:48.650 --> 00:25:52.820
it's just an internal process
that's triggered in the brain.

00:25:52.820 --> 00:25:54.860
This is an extraordinarily
effective treatment

00:25:54.860 --> 00:25:56.940
for treatment-resistant depression.

00:25:56.940 --> 00:25:58.610
At the same time, I find it [chuckles]

00:25:58.610 --> 00:26:02.235
as heartening as it is to
see patients respond to this

00:26:02.235 --> 00:26:06.210
who have severe depression,
I'm also frustrated by it.

00:26:06.210 --> 00:26:09.730
Why can't we do something
more precise than this,

00:26:09.730 --> 00:26:11.650
for these very severe cases?

00:26:11.650 --> 00:26:15.000
And people have sought
for decades to understand,

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.410
how is it that a seizure is leading

00:26:17.410 --> 00:26:19.080
to the relief of depression?

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:20.460
And we don't know the answer yet.

00:26:20.460 --> 00:26:21.570
We would love to do that.

00:26:21.570 --> 00:26:23.450
People are working hard on that,

00:26:23.450 --> 00:26:26.366
but that is a treatment
that does work too.

00:26:26.366 --> 00:26:28.270
In all of these cases
though in psychiatry,

00:26:28.270 --> 00:26:30.680
the frustrating thing
is that we don't have

00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:34.840
the level of understanding
that a cardiologist has

00:26:34.840 --> 00:26:35.950
in thinking about the heart.

00:26:35.950 --> 00:26:38.240
You know, the heart is,
we now know it's a pump.

00:26:38.240 --> 00:26:40.980
It's pumping blood. and so
you can look at everything

00:26:40.980 --> 00:26:43.430
about how it's working or not working,

00:26:43.430 --> 00:26:47.170
in terms of that frame,
it's clearly a pump.

00:26:47.170 --> 00:26:49.240
We don't really have that level

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:53.653
of, what is the circuit really
there for in psychiatry?

00:26:55.256 --> 00:26:56.930
And that's what is missing.

00:26:56.930 --> 00:26:58.640
That's what we need to find,

00:26:58.640 --> 00:27:02.200
so we can design truly effective
and specific treatments.

00:27:02.200 --> 00:27:05.970
- So, what are the pieces
that are going to be required

00:27:05.970 --> 00:27:10.970
to cure autism, cure
Parkinson's, cure schizophrenia?

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:16.270
I would imagine there are several
elements and 'beens here',

00:27:16.270 --> 00:27:18.860
understanding the natural biology,

00:27:18.860 --> 00:27:21.450
understanding what the
activity patterns are,

00:27:21.450 --> 00:27:24.430
how to modify those, maybe
you could just tell us

00:27:24.430 --> 00:27:29.163
what you think, what is the
Bento Box of the perfect cure?

00:27:30.070 --> 00:27:32.670
- I think the first thing
we need is understanding.

00:27:34.140 --> 00:27:35.560
Almost every psychiatric treatment

00:27:35.560 --> 00:27:37.670
has been serendipitously identified,

00:27:37.670 --> 00:27:41.510
just noting by chance that
something that was done

00:27:41.510 --> 00:27:44.200
for some person also had a side effect-

00:27:44.200 --> 00:27:45.090
- Like lithium or something-

00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:46.800
- Like lithium, is a good example.

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:49.268
- Is it true that it was
the urine of guinea pigs

00:27:49.268 --> 00:27:50.180
[Karl laughs]
given lithium

00:27:50.180 --> 00:27:52.880
that was given to manic patients
that made them not manic?

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:53.750
Is that true?

00:27:53.750 --> 00:27:55.220
- I don't have firsthand
knowledge of that,

00:27:55.220 --> 00:27:57.280
but I would defer that,

00:27:57.280 --> 00:27:59.700
but it's true for
essentially every treatment,

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:03.090
that the antidepressants originally arose

00:28:03.090 --> 00:28:05.561
as anti-tuberculosis drugs, for example.

00:28:05.561 --> 00:28:06.394
- I did not know that.

00:28:06.394 --> 00:28:10.520
- Yeah, and so this is a
classic example for illnesses

00:28:10.520 --> 00:28:12.800
across all of psychiatry,

00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:14.390
and of course there's
the seizures as well.

00:28:14.390 --> 00:28:16.430
That was noticed that
patients who had epilepsy,

00:28:16.430 --> 00:28:19.380
they had a seizure there
and also had depression,

00:28:19.380 --> 00:28:21.440
that they became much,
at least for awhile,

00:28:21.440 --> 00:28:23.630
they were improved after that seizure.

00:28:23.630 --> 00:28:24.463
- That's amazing.

00:28:24.463 --> 00:28:26.491
I don't want to take you
off course of the question

00:28:26.491 --> 00:28:27.324
answering the question I asked,

00:28:27.324 --> 00:28:31.320
but I've heard before that if
autistic children get a fever,

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:33.850
that their symptoms improve, is that true?

00:28:33.850 --> 00:28:37.870
- I've done a fair bit
of work with autism.

00:28:37.870 --> 00:28:40.230
In my clinical practice,
I work with adult autism

00:28:40.230 --> 00:28:42.460
and I have heard statements like that

00:28:42.460 --> 00:28:45.773
and descriptions like that from
patients and their families.

00:28:48.040 --> 00:28:50.300
That is very hard to study quantitatively

00:28:50.300 --> 00:28:52.600
because often with the
children, you have this

00:28:54.010 --> 00:28:55.840
not as quantitative as you'd like

00:28:55.840 --> 00:28:59.750
collection of symptom
information from home.

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:02.000
But I have heard that enough that I think

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:03.800
there may well be something to that.

00:29:07.104 --> 00:29:08.960
And anytime you have a
fever, what's going on?

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:11.527
Well, we know all the cells in the brain,

00:29:11.527 --> 00:29:13.580
and I know this as an electrophysiologist,

00:29:13.580 --> 00:29:15.620
if you just change the
temperature by a few degrees,

00:29:15.620 --> 00:29:17.570
everything changes about how neurons work

00:29:17.570 --> 00:29:19.510
and that's even just a single neuron.

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:22.420
It's even more likely to
be complex and different

00:29:22.420 --> 00:29:25.120
with a circuit of neurons that
are all affecting each other.

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:26.770
Just elevate the temperature a little bit,

00:29:26.770 --> 00:29:27.680
everything's different.

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:30.500
And so, it's plausible for sure,

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:32.950
that things like that
could happen and do happen.

00:29:34.620 --> 00:29:37.693
And yet, when you think about
autism, to take your example,

00:29:39.170 --> 00:29:40.800
yes, we see changes,

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:45.260
but what is the elements of
the brain that's analogous

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:46.630
to the pumping heart?

00:29:46.630 --> 00:29:49.313
When we think about the
symptoms of depression,

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:53.990
we think about motivation
and dopamine neurons.

00:29:53.990 --> 00:29:57.223
When we think about autism,
it's a little more challenging.

00:29:58.240 --> 00:30:03.240
There's a deficit in social interaction

00:30:03.500 --> 00:30:04.963
and in communication.

00:30:06.220 --> 00:30:07.397
And so where is that?

00:30:07.397 --> 00:30:09.870
[chuckles] Where is that situated?

00:30:09.870 --> 00:30:14.870
What is the key principle
governing the social interaction?

00:30:15.630 --> 00:30:17.780
This is where we need the basic science

00:30:17.780 --> 00:30:19.400
to bring us a step forward,

00:30:19.400 --> 00:30:21.830
so we can say okay, this is
the process that's going on.

00:30:21.830 --> 00:30:25.180
This is what's needed for
the incredibly complex task

00:30:25.180 --> 00:30:27.010
of social interaction,

00:30:27.010 --> 00:30:30.560
where you've got incredibly
rich data streams of sound

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:33.130
and meaning, eye contact, body movement,

00:30:33.130 --> 00:30:34.260
and that's just for one person.

00:30:34.260 --> 00:30:36.130
What if there's a group of people?

00:30:36.130 --> 00:30:39.587
This is overwhelming
for people with autism.

00:30:39.587 --> 00:30:41.940
What's the unifying thing there?

00:30:41.940 --> 00:30:43.534
It's a lot of information,

00:30:43.534 --> 00:30:48.520
and that maybe is unmatched
in any realm of biology,

00:30:48.520 --> 00:30:49.900
the amount of information coming in

00:30:49.900 --> 00:30:50.980
through a social interaction,

00:30:50.980 --> 00:30:52.903
particularly with words and language.

00:30:53.830 --> 00:30:57.030
And so then, that turns our
attention as neuroscientists,

00:30:57.030 --> 00:31:00.110
we think, okay, let's think
about the parts of the brain

00:31:00.110 --> 00:31:04.800
that are involved in dealing with merging

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:08.330
complex data streams that
are very high in bit rate

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:11.853
that need to be fused together
into a unitary concept.

00:31:12.740 --> 00:31:15.346
And that starts to guide us,

00:31:15.346 --> 00:31:17.537
and we know other animals
are social in their own way,

00:31:17.537 --> 00:31:19.080
and we can study those animals.

00:31:19.080 --> 00:31:21.150
And so that's how I think about it.

00:31:21.150 --> 00:31:22.410
There's hope for the future,

00:31:22.410 --> 00:31:25.670
thinking about the symptoms
as an engineer might,

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:30.190
and trying to identify the
circuits that are likely working

00:31:30.190 --> 00:31:32.410
to make this typical behavior happen,

00:31:32.410 --> 00:31:35.150
and that will help us understand
how it becomes atypical.

00:31:35.150 --> 00:31:37.530
- So that seems like the first to me,

00:31:37.530 --> 00:31:41.010
the first been of this,
what I call the Bento Box

00:31:41.010 --> 00:31:43.020
for lack of a better analogy,

00:31:43.020 --> 00:31:44.690
that we need to know the circuits.

00:31:44.690 --> 00:31:47.870
We need to know the cells
in the various brain regions

00:31:47.870 --> 00:31:49.608
and end portions of the body

00:31:49.608 --> 00:31:52.280
and how they connect to one another,

00:31:52.280 --> 00:31:54.500
and what the patterns of activity are

00:31:54.500 --> 00:31:57.820
under a normal 'healthy interaction'.

00:31:57.820 --> 00:31:59.100
- [Karl] Yeah.

00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:04.100
- If we understand that, then
it seems that the next step,

00:32:04.270 --> 00:32:06.480
which of course could be
carried out in parallel, right?

00:32:06.480 --> 00:32:09.130
Though that work can
be done alongside work

00:32:09.130 --> 00:32:13.110
where various elements within
those circuits are tweaked

00:32:13.110 --> 00:32:16.190
just right, like the tuning
of a piano in the subtle way,

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:18.310
or maybe even like the
replacement of a whole set of keys

00:32:18.310 --> 00:32:20.656
if the piano is lacking keys, so to speak.

00:32:20.656 --> 00:32:21.490
- Right.

00:32:21.490 --> 00:32:22.660
- You've been very involved

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:24.993
in trying to generate those tools.

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:29.670
Tell us about channelopsins,

00:32:29.670 --> 00:32:34.440
why you created them,
and where they're at now

00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:38.570
in the laboratory and
perhaps also in the clinic.

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:42.146
- Well, first of all, I
give nature the credit

00:32:42.146 --> 00:32:43.970
for creating channelrhodopsins.

00:32:43.970 --> 00:32:48.150
These are beautiful little
proteins that are made by algae,

00:32:48.150 --> 00:32:50.310
single-celled green algae.

00:32:50.310 --> 00:32:53.190
And there's a great story in basic science

00:32:53.190 --> 00:32:57.510
that our understanding of animal behavior,

00:32:57.510 --> 00:33:00.710
sensation, cognition
and action in our brains

00:33:00.710 --> 00:33:05.710
all the way back to a botanist
in the 1850s and 1860s

00:33:06.120 --> 00:33:08.550
in Russia, is where the story begins.

00:33:08.550 --> 00:33:12.340
So this was a botanist
named Andrei Famintsyn

00:33:12.340 --> 00:33:14.900
who worked at St. Petersburg,

00:33:14.900 --> 00:33:19.900
and he had noticed in the
river near his laboratory,

00:33:19.970 --> 00:33:23.700
that there were algae
that he could look at

00:33:23.700 --> 00:33:25.170
in a dish, in a saucer.

00:33:25.170 --> 00:33:27.270
He could put them there and he had light

00:33:27.270 --> 00:33:28.493
shining from the side.

00:33:29.360 --> 00:33:33.770
The green tinge in the saucer of water

00:33:34.640 --> 00:33:38.820
would move to a particular
distance from the light

00:33:38.820 --> 00:33:40.420
that he was shining from the side,

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:42.470
which was an amazing thing.

00:33:42.470 --> 00:33:44.880
If he made the light brighter,

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:47.100
the green tinge would
back off a little bit

00:33:47.100 --> 00:33:50.430
to a more optimal location,
so just the right light level.

00:33:50.430 --> 00:33:53.020
So this was plant behavior.

00:33:53.020 --> 00:33:54.690
It was light-driven plant behavior,

00:33:54.690 --> 00:33:56.210
and he delves into this a little bit.

00:33:56.210 --> 00:33:58.730
He identified that with microscopy,

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:01.060
he could see that there were
little single-cell algae

00:34:01.060 --> 00:34:05.380
with flagella that were swimming
to the right light level.

00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:07.920
So behaving plants, and
this has been the secret

00:34:07.920 --> 00:34:10.900
that's helped us unlock so many principles

00:34:10.900 --> 00:34:12.840
of animal behavior.

00:34:12.840 --> 00:34:14.633
So turns out,

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:20.420
these algae achieve this amazing results

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:25.420
with a single gene that
encodes a single protein.

00:34:25.950 --> 00:34:26.783
What's a protein?

00:34:26.783 --> 00:34:30.350
It's just a little bio-molecule
that does a job in a cell.

00:34:30.350 --> 00:34:34.280
And these are proteins that
sit in the surface of cells

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:36.280
in their surface membrane,

00:34:36.280 --> 00:34:39.490
and when a photon, a
light particle hits them,

00:34:39.490 --> 00:34:42.280
they open a little pore, a
little hole in the membrane

00:34:42.280 --> 00:34:45.540
and charged particles, ions like sodium

00:34:45.540 --> 00:34:47.363
rush across the pore.

00:34:48.260 --> 00:34:49.670
Now, why do they do that?

00:34:49.670 --> 00:34:53.360
They do that to guide their
flagella, that signal coming in,

00:34:53.360 --> 00:34:55.230
those ions coming in through the pore

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:58.500
in response to light,
guide their flagella motor,

00:34:58.500 --> 00:35:02.383
that guides them to a
particular spot in the saucer.

00:35:03.710 --> 00:35:06.830
Now, that's plant
behavior, but it turns out,

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:09.910
as you know, this movement
of ions across the membrane,

00:35:09.910 --> 00:35:12.500
this happens to also be a neural code

00:35:12.500 --> 00:35:15.120
in our brains for on or off.

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:18.190
Sodium ions rushing into
the cells, turns them on.

00:35:18.190 --> 00:35:21.470
It makes them fire away, fire
action potentials communicate

00:35:21.470 --> 00:35:24.500
to the next cell down the chain,

00:35:24.500 --> 00:35:27.020
and this is an amazing opportunity

00:35:27.020 --> 00:35:31.320
because we can borrow these proteins.

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:32.850
In fact, we can take the gene

00:35:32.850 --> 00:35:35.360
that directs the creation of the protein,

00:35:35.360 --> 00:35:37.580
and we can use genetic
tricks, modern genetic tricks

00:35:37.580 --> 00:35:42.273
to put that gene into neurons
in the brains of mammals,

00:35:44.002 --> 00:35:46.570
and then use light to turn those cells,

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:49.290
the specific cells that
we put this gene into,

00:35:49.290 --> 00:35:50.250
turn them on.

00:35:50.250 --> 00:35:52.980
There are other opsins, we call them,

00:35:52.980 --> 00:35:55.300
that you can use to turn cells off.

00:35:55.300 --> 00:35:57.920
It's all fast, real time.

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:00.700
You can play in patterns
of activity in real time

00:36:00.700 --> 00:36:04.000
into cells or kinds of
cells, just as a conductor

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:05.770
elicits the music from the orchestra,

00:36:05.770 --> 00:36:07.700
the strings and the woodwinds.

00:36:07.700 --> 00:36:09.800
And you can see what matters.

00:36:09.800 --> 00:36:12.270
What matters for sensation,
what matters for cognition,

00:36:12.270 --> 00:36:15.360
what matters for action, and
we call this optogenetics.

00:36:15.360 --> 00:36:18.570
- Beautiful, and I must
say it was quite an honor

00:36:18.570 --> 00:36:22.020
and a privilege to watch optogenetics move

00:36:22.020 --> 00:36:26.820
from idea to discovery to the laboratory.

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:28.783
I think we were postdocs at the same time,

00:36:28.783 --> 00:36:29.616
- We were, huh?

00:36:29.616 --> 00:36:32.340
- which is living proof that
people move at different rates,

00:36:32.340 --> 00:36:36.015
because [laughs] it's a joke
at my expense by the way,

00:36:36.015 --> 00:36:37.750
[Karl laughing]

00:36:37.750 --> 00:36:38.810
but it's really-

00:36:38.810 --> 00:36:39.643
- We end up in the same spot. [laughs]

00:36:39.643 --> 00:36:41.770
- That's right, [laughs]
yeah, more or less.

00:36:41.770 --> 00:36:44.210
Physically, if not professionally,

00:36:44.210 --> 00:36:48.460
but nonetheless, it's been
a marvelous story thus far.

00:36:48.460 --> 00:36:49.960
And I'd like to...

00:36:49.960 --> 00:36:50.793
Maybe you could give us...

00:36:50.793 --> 00:36:53.270
I'd like to just touch
on a couple examples

00:36:53.270 --> 00:36:56.850
of where the technology
resides in laboratories now,

00:36:56.850 --> 00:36:59.230
so maybe the range of animals
that it's being used in,

00:36:59.230 --> 00:37:00.710
and some of the phenomenon

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:05.630
that channelrhodopsins
and their related genes

00:37:05.630 --> 00:37:09.853
and proteins are starting
to elicit, what you've seen,

00:37:10.850 --> 00:37:13.460
and then I'd like to talk
about their applicability

00:37:13.460 --> 00:37:16.950
to the clinic, which is I
think the bigger mission,

00:37:16.950 --> 00:37:18.040
if you will.

00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:18.873
- Yeah.

00:37:18.873 --> 00:37:22.700
So this whole thing, you know,

00:37:22.700 --> 00:37:25.830
it's been about, now going on 17 years

00:37:25.830 --> 00:37:28.460
that we've been putting
channelrhodopsins into neurons.

00:37:28.460 --> 00:37:31.803
It started just like Andre
Famintsyn's work in a dish,

00:37:33.733 --> 00:37:34.776
that was in 2004.

00:37:34.776 --> 00:37:38.220
In 2007, we were putting
these into behaving mice,

00:37:38.220 --> 00:37:42.000
and we were able to with
a flick of a switch,

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.710
cause them to move one
direction or another,

00:37:44.710 --> 00:37:45.900
by 2009-

00:37:45.900 --> 00:37:48.360
- So basically, you're
controlling the mouse's behavior?

00:37:48.360 --> 00:37:49.650
- Yeah, exactly. In real time.

00:37:49.650 --> 00:37:51.310
So we could make a mouse
that was just sitting there

00:37:51.310 --> 00:37:54.670
doing nothing, to then turn
left very consistently,

00:37:54.670 --> 00:37:55.990
in fact, go around in a circle

00:37:55.990 --> 00:37:58.100
and as soon as we turn off
the light, it would stop.

00:37:58.100 --> 00:37:59.773
That was an eye-opening moment.

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:05.030
It took really a few years
to make optogenetics work.

00:38:05.030 --> 00:38:08.130
There was a lot of putting all the...

00:38:08.130 --> 00:38:09.680
There are a lot of problems
that had to be solved.

00:38:09.680 --> 00:38:14.190
These channelrhodopsins
actually don't move many ions.

00:38:14.190 --> 00:38:17.100
They have a small current,
small conductance, as we say.

00:38:17.100 --> 00:38:20.140
And so we had to figure out
ways to pack a lot of them

00:38:20.140 --> 00:38:23.470
into cells without damaging cells,

00:38:23.470 --> 00:38:25.210
and still make them targetable,

00:38:25.210 --> 00:38:27.150
so we don't want them to
just be in all the cells,

00:38:27.150 --> 00:38:29.530
'cause then it becomes
just like an electrode.

00:38:29.530 --> 00:38:31.260
You're just stimulating all
the cells that are nearby.

00:38:31.260 --> 00:38:33.650
We had to keep that specificity,

00:38:33.650 --> 00:38:37.540
make them targetable to just
one kind of cell or another,

00:38:37.540 --> 00:38:39.470
while still packing in
large numbers of them

00:38:39.470 --> 00:38:40.970
into those cells.

00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:43.490
And we had to get in the light
in safe and specific ways,

00:38:43.490 --> 00:38:46.420
and so it took probably
about four or five years

00:38:46.420 --> 00:38:50.620
to really create optogenetics
between 2004 and 2009.

00:38:50.620 --> 00:38:51.840
By the end of that time though,

00:38:51.840 --> 00:38:56.840
we had all the basic light
delivery, gene delivery,

00:38:57.100 --> 00:39:00.510
principles worked out, and
people started to apply

00:39:00.510 --> 00:39:05.510
the technology to fish, to rats, to mice,

00:39:05.570 --> 00:39:09.890
to non-human primates like monkeys,

00:39:09.890 --> 00:39:14.270
and just a couple months ago,

00:39:14.270 --> 00:39:17.070
my colleague, Botond Rosca in Switzerland,

00:39:17.070 --> 00:39:19.890
succeeded in putting channelrhodopsins

00:39:19.890 --> 00:39:21.690
into the eyes of human beings

00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:23.870
and making a blind person to see.

00:39:23.870 --> 00:39:25.813
And so that's pretty cool.

00:39:26.920 --> 00:39:30.690
This was a patient with
retinal degeneration,

00:39:30.690 --> 00:39:32.960
and he provided a channelrhodopsin

00:39:32.960 --> 00:39:34.667
into the eye of this patient

00:39:34.667 --> 00:39:36.910
and was able to confer
some light sensitivity

00:39:36.910 --> 00:39:38.820
onto this patient that
wasn't there before.

00:39:38.820 --> 00:39:40.680
- An amazing paper and discovery.

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:42.120
I realize it was one patient,

00:39:42.120 --> 00:39:44.110
but it's such an important milestone.

00:39:44.110 --> 00:39:46.870
- Well, as you say, it's
a very important milestone

00:39:46.870 --> 00:39:50.850
and the history of that is very deep.

00:39:50.850 --> 00:39:53.520
Almost 10 years earlier,
Botond Rosca and I

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:57.080
had published a paper in
science in human retina,

00:39:57.080 --> 00:40:00.640
but X plants taken from cadavers
from someone who had died,

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:02.843
the living retina taken out,

00:40:03.750 --> 00:40:07.130
opsins put into this retinal tissue

00:40:07.130 --> 00:40:09.640
and showing that it worked,
recording from the cells

00:40:09.640 --> 00:40:12.210
showing that in these
human retinal neurons,

00:40:12.210 --> 00:40:14.660
that you could get light responses.

00:40:14.660 --> 00:40:16.770
But then, from that moment,

00:40:16.770 --> 00:40:20.090
almost 10 years of how
clinical development goes,

00:40:20.090 --> 00:40:21.500
and this is a gene therapy

00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:24.060
and so you've got all the regulations

00:40:24.060 --> 00:40:25.270
and concerns and all that.

00:40:25.270 --> 00:40:27.830
It took almost 10 years
to get to this point now

00:40:27.830 --> 00:40:30.890
where a living human being
has a new functionality

00:40:30.890 --> 00:40:32.860
that wasn't there before.

00:40:32.860 --> 00:40:34.773
Now, that's incredibly inspiring,

00:40:37.092 --> 00:40:38.330
and it's a beautiful thing.

00:40:38.330 --> 00:40:39.163
I would say though,

00:40:39.163 --> 00:40:43.750
that the broader
significance of optogenetics

00:40:43.750 --> 00:40:47.350
is really still understanding,
because once you understand

00:40:47.350 --> 00:40:50.520
how the circuitry works and
which cells actually matter,

00:40:50.520 --> 00:40:54.770
then any kind of treatment
becomes more grounded and logical

00:40:54.770 --> 00:40:57.210
and specific and principled.

00:40:57.210 --> 00:40:59.390
And whether it's a
medication, or a talk therapy

00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:00.820
or brain stimulation treatment

00:41:00.820 --> 00:41:03.510
with electrical or magnetic means,

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:05.640
if you actually know what matters,

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:06.810
[chuckles] that is incredibly powerful.

00:41:06.810 --> 00:41:07.643
And I think,

00:41:10.750 --> 00:41:14.610
not intended to disparage
the beautiful retinal work

00:41:14.610 --> 00:41:17.760
and conferring vision on
someone who couldn't see,

00:41:17.760 --> 00:41:19.110
of course that's wonderful,

00:41:21.130 --> 00:41:22.570
and that's direct what you might call

00:41:22.570 --> 00:41:24.180
direct optogenetics in patients.

00:41:24.180 --> 00:41:27.440
Indirect is everything that
comes from understanding.

00:41:27.440 --> 00:41:30.390
Okay, we know these cells
matter now, for this symptom.

00:41:30.390 --> 00:41:33.070
Well, how can we target those cells

00:41:33.070 --> 00:41:35.610
and help them work better
in patients by any means?

00:41:35.610 --> 00:41:37.670
And I think that's the
broader significance

00:41:37.670 --> 00:41:39.314
of optogenetics, clinically.

00:41:39.314 --> 00:41:40.760
- I know Botond well,

00:41:40.760 --> 00:41:45.760
and you and Botond share
this incredible big vision,

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:50.380
that I think only a clinician
can really understand,

00:41:50.380 --> 00:41:54.610
being in close contact within
the suffering of patients

00:41:54.610 --> 00:41:57.680
as a ultimate motivator of
developing technologies,

00:41:57.680 --> 00:42:00.380
which makes me have to ask,

00:42:00.380 --> 00:42:02.940
did you decide to become a scientist

00:42:02.940 --> 00:42:06.561
to find cures for mental disease?

00:42:06.561 --> 00:42:10.050
- [chuckles] No, I didn't.

00:42:10.050 --> 00:42:12.116
It's a really important
question to actually look back

00:42:12.116 --> 00:42:16.510
and see the steps that brought
you to a particular place.

00:42:16.510 --> 00:42:20.670
And that was not what brought
me initially to science

00:42:20.670 --> 00:42:23.470
and it's okay I think,
to embrace [chuckles]

00:42:23.470 --> 00:42:27.400
the twists and turns
that life brings to you,

00:42:27.400 --> 00:42:29.090
but I was always interested in the brain.

00:42:29.090 --> 00:42:32.650
And so, that was something
that for me started

00:42:32.650 --> 00:42:35.300
from a very early age.

00:42:35.300 --> 00:42:36.871
We talked about being introspective.

00:42:36.871 --> 00:42:41.530
I noticed very early on I
had a deep love of poetry

00:42:41.530 --> 00:42:45.603
and stories, and I was a voracious reader,

00:42:46.620 --> 00:42:51.620
and I was amazed by how
words could make me feel

00:42:52.900 --> 00:42:54.555
in particular ways.

00:42:54.555 --> 00:42:58.420
Even separate from their, of
course, dictionary meanings,

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:01.190
the rhythm, and how they work together,

00:43:01.190 --> 00:43:03.260
even separate from meaning.

00:43:03.260 --> 00:43:07.450
And I was stunned by poets that
could use words in new ways

00:43:07.450 --> 00:43:10.480
that were even divorced
from their meaning at all,

00:43:10.480 --> 00:43:12.500
and yet could still
trigger specific emotions.

00:43:12.500 --> 00:43:14.853
And this was always fascinating to me.

00:43:15.820 --> 00:43:19.830
So, I wanted to understand that,

00:43:19.830 --> 00:43:23.320
and so I was interested and I
became interested in the brain

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:25.210
and I thought, well, I'm
going to to have to study

00:43:25.210 --> 00:43:30.210
the human brain, because only
human beings can describe

00:43:31.220 --> 00:43:33.233
what's going on inside enough.

00:43:34.110 --> 00:43:38.193
So in college, I began to
steer myself toward medicine,

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:41.930
with the idea of becoming a neurosurgeon.

00:43:41.930 --> 00:43:46.930
And so I came here to medical school,

00:43:47.120 --> 00:43:48.933
and did an MD PhD program,

00:43:50.260 --> 00:43:52.110
planning neurosurgery all the way through.

00:43:52.110 --> 00:43:55.840
The first rotation I did at
the end of medical school,

00:43:55.840 --> 00:43:57.540
as you know, you do rotations,

00:43:57.540 --> 00:43:59.090
you go through different specialties,

00:43:59.090 --> 00:44:01.110
and some of these are required rotations,

00:44:01.110 --> 00:44:02.870
everybody has to do this summary elective

00:44:02.870 --> 00:44:04.853
where you can pick what you want to do.

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:08.440
I elected to do the
neurosurgery first, [chuckles]

00:44:08.440 --> 00:44:09.810
even before regular surgery.

00:44:09.810 --> 00:44:11.710
I was that sure I wanted
to do it, and I loved it.

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:13.410
I had a fantastic time.

00:44:13.410 --> 00:44:17.630
There was an amazing patient
who had a thalamic damage,

00:44:17.630 --> 00:44:19.070
and there was a neglect syndrome

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:22.630
where the patient was not
able to be aware of something

00:44:22.630 --> 00:44:24.860
that was right in front of him-

00:44:24.860 --> 00:44:26.050
- Even though their
vision was perfectly fine?

00:44:26.050 --> 00:44:28.603
- Even though their vision
was perfectly fine, exactly.

00:44:30.210 --> 00:44:31.480
And I loved the operating room,

00:44:31.480 --> 00:44:36.307
I loved the rhythm of suturing
and the precision of it,

00:44:36.307 --> 00:44:39.053
and I loved being able to
help patients immediately,

00:44:40.100 --> 00:44:44.243
but then a required
rotation was in psychiatry,

00:44:45.370 --> 00:44:48.470
which I was not looking forward to at all.

00:44:48.470 --> 00:44:51.590
And that completely reset my whole life,

00:44:51.590 --> 00:44:54.190
that experience in psychiatry.

00:44:54.190 --> 00:44:56.610
And it was at that moment that I saw

00:44:56.610 --> 00:45:00.170
this is first of all, the greatest need,

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:01.920
the depth of suffering

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:04.713
and the depth of the mystery together.

00:45:05.850 --> 00:45:09.240
And also it was, I almost feel
a little guilty about this.

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:11.193
It's so interesting too.

00:45:11.193 --> 00:45:13.890
Yes, we can help.

00:45:13.890 --> 00:45:17.260
Yes, there's need, but as a scientist,

00:45:17.260 --> 00:45:20.850
this is amazing, that someone's
reality can be different

00:45:20.850 --> 00:45:24.350
from my own, with everything physically,

00:45:24.350 --> 00:45:29.100
as far as we can tell the same
with the measures we have,

00:45:29.100 --> 00:45:30.520
and yet we've got a different reality.

00:45:30.520 --> 00:45:34.060
That is an amazing thing,
and if we can understand that

00:45:34.060 --> 00:45:38.360
and help these people,
that would be just more

00:45:38.360 --> 00:45:39.193
than anybody could ask for.

00:45:39.193 --> 00:45:42.500
And so that's how I ended
up taking this path,

00:45:42.500 --> 00:45:46.300
just a required rotation in psychiatry.

00:45:46.300 --> 00:45:47.970
- It all started with poetry?

00:45:47.970 --> 00:45:49.390
- And it started with poetry.

00:45:49.390 --> 00:45:52.350
- Out of respect for poetry,

00:45:52.350 --> 00:45:54.950
are there any favorites
that you spend time with

00:45:55.920 --> 00:45:57.540
on a regular basis?

00:45:57.540 --> 00:46:01.950
- I mean, the ones who
got me down this path

00:46:01.950 --> 00:46:04.943
early on, I remember in
childhood and high school,

00:46:05.990 --> 00:46:08.443
Borges had an immense influence on me.

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:14.100
I studied Spanish all the way
through and reading his work.

00:46:14.100 --> 00:46:15.600
He was a great writer.

00:46:15.600 --> 00:46:17.600
He wrote both in English and in Spanish

00:46:17.600 --> 00:46:20.100
and being able to appreciate his poetry

00:46:20.100 --> 00:46:23.170
both in English and in Spanish
was a pretty amazing thing.

00:46:23.170 --> 00:46:25.720
Not many poets can do that.

00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:26.860
- You're bilingual?

00:46:26.860 --> 00:46:28.330
- I'm not, I wouldn't say.

00:46:28.330 --> 00:46:31.500
Now I became, at one point
I was effectively fluent

00:46:31.500 --> 00:46:34.550
in Spanish, and I'm pretty
good with medical Spanish still

00:46:34.550 --> 00:46:39.540
because we use Spanish all
the time in the clinic here.

00:46:39.540 --> 00:46:42.510
I wouldn't claim full fluency,
but it's something I can

00:46:42.510 --> 00:46:44.424
definitely use all the time.

00:46:44.424 --> 00:46:45.950
And that's been very
helpful in the clinic.

00:46:45.950 --> 00:46:47.030
- Yeah, Borges is wonderful.

00:46:47.030 --> 00:46:49.870
As the son of an Argentine,
I grew up hearing about it

00:46:49.870 --> 00:46:53.600
and I learned that Borges'
favorite city was Geneva.

00:46:53.600 --> 00:46:56.380
So I spent time in Geneva
only for that reason.

00:46:56.380 --> 00:46:57.294
It's also turns out

00:46:57.294 --> 00:46:58.420
[Karl laughs]
to be an interesting city.

00:46:58.420 --> 00:46:59.253
- Yes.

00:47:00.240 --> 00:47:04.770
- So you developed
methods to control neurons

00:47:04.770 --> 00:47:09.220
with these algae proteins using light?

00:47:09.220 --> 00:47:10.300
- Yeah.

00:47:10.300 --> 00:47:14.380
- In 2015, there was what I
thought was a very nice article

00:47:14.380 --> 00:47:17.230
published in the New
Yorker, describing your work

00:47:17.230 --> 00:47:19.950
and the current state of your work

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:21.640
in the laboratory and the clinic,

00:47:21.640 --> 00:47:24.470
and an interaction with a patient.

00:47:24.470 --> 00:47:28.350
So this as I recall, a woman
who was severely depressed,

00:47:28.350 --> 00:47:30.390
and you reported in that article

00:47:30.390 --> 00:47:32.500
some of the discussion with this patient,

00:47:32.500 --> 00:47:34.860
and then in real time,

00:47:34.860 --> 00:47:38.280
increased the activation of
the so-called vagus nerve,

00:47:38.280 --> 00:47:40.410
this 10th cranial nerve that
extends out of the skull

00:47:40.410 --> 00:47:43.323
and innervates many of
the viscera and body.

00:47:45.570 --> 00:47:48.880
What is the potential
for channelrhodopsins

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:52.330
or related types of algae engineering

00:47:52.330 --> 00:47:56.200
to be used to manipulate the vagus?

00:47:56.200 --> 00:47:57.390
Because I believe in that instance,

00:47:57.390 --> 00:47:59.020
it wasn't channelopsin stimulation,

00:47:59.020 --> 00:48:00.760
it was electrical stimulation, right?

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:02.280
Or to manipulate for instance,

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:04.880
a very small localized
region of the brain?

00:48:04.880 --> 00:48:07.460
Let me frame it a little bit differently

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:09.933
in light of what we were talking
about a couple minutes ago.

00:48:10.850 --> 00:48:14.030
My understanding is that if
somebody has severe depression

00:48:14.030 --> 00:48:15.790
and they take any number

00:48:15.790 --> 00:48:19.680
of the available pharmaceutical
agents that are out there,

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:22.920
SSRI, serotonergic agents,
increased dopamine,

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:26.400
increased whatever, that
sometimes they experience relief,

00:48:26.400 --> 00:48:28.250
but they're often serious side effects.

00:48:28.250 --> 00:48:29.970
Sometimes they don't experience relief,

00:48:29.970 --> 00:48:32.120
but as I understand it,

00:48:32.120 --> 00:48:35.690
channelopsins and their related
technology, in principle,

00:48:35.690 --> 00:48:40.670
would allow you to turn on
or off the specific regions

00:48:40.670 --> 00:48:43.420
of the brain that lead to
the depressive symptoms,

00:48:43.420 --> 00:48:45.530
or maybe you turn up a happiness circuit,

00:48:45.530 --> 00:48:49.820
or a positive anticipation circuit.

00:48:49.820 --> 00:48:53.430
Where are we at now in terms
of bringing this technology

00:48:53.430 --> 00:48:55.010
to the nervous system?

00:48:55.010 --> 00:48:58.960
And let's start with the body,
and then move into the skull.

00:48:58.960 --> 00:48:59.793
- Yup.

00:48:59.793 --> 00:49:01.470
So starting with the
body is a good example

00:49:01.470 --> 00:49:04.710
because it highlights the opportunity

00:49:04.710 --> 00:49:06.740
and how far we have to go.

00:49:06.740 --> 00:49:09.770
So let's take this example
of vagus nerve stimulation.

00:49:09.770 --> 00:49:12.140
So the vagus nerve, it's
the 10th cranial nerve.

00:49:12.140 --> 00:49:14.130
It comes from the brain, it goes down

00:49:14.130 --> 00:49:16.480
and innervates the heart
and innervates the gut.

00:49:16.480 --> 00:49:18.910
And by innervate, I mean it
sends little connections down

00:49:18.910 --> 00:49:22.182
to help guide what happens in these organs

00:49:22.182 --> 00:49:24.603
in the abdomen and chest.

00:49:25.870 --> 00:49:27.860
It also collects information back,

00:49:27.860 --> 00:49:30.760
and there's information coming
back from all those organs

00:49:30.760 --> 00:49:32.720
that also go through this vagus nerve,

00:49:32.720 --> 00:49:35.230
the 10th cranial nerve, back to the brain.

00:49:35.230 --> 00:49:39.197
And so this is somewhat of a
super highway to the brain,

00:49:39.197 --> 00:49:40.320
and it was the idea.

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:43.210
And maybe the idea is maybe
we could put a little cuff,

