01:00:54.990 --> 01:00:56.093
'cause in your book,

01:00:57.110 --> 01:01:00.080
you describe the incredible complexity

01:01:00.080 --> 01:01:01.900
of social interactions.

01:01:01.900 --> 01:01:04.380
And at one point,

01:01:04.380 --> 01:01:09.150
you describe the incredible
amount of information

01:01:09.150 --> 01:01:12.340
that the eyes inform about the brain

01:01:12.340 --> 01:01:14.950
and the context of
somebody's inner experience,

01:01:14.950 --> 01:01:16.639
whether depressed or happy or otherwise.

01:01:16.639 --> 01:01:17.472
- Yeah.

01:01:17.472 --> 01:01:20.954
- I want to make sure that we
get back to how to maneuver

01:01:20.954 --> 01:01:23.290
and manipulate the nervous system

01:01:23.290 --> 01:01:24.790
for the sake of mental health.

01:01:26.204 --> 01:01:28.870
But, what are you looking for?

01:01:28.870 --> 01:01:30.300
So as a vision scientist,

01:01:30.300 --> 01:01:33.190
I think pupils dilating
is a sign of arousal,

01:01:33.190 --> 01:01:35.810
but that could be a positive
arousal, positive valence,

01:01:35.810 --> 01:01:38.310
like excitement, or it could be terror.

01:01:38.310 --> 01:01:39.143
- Yeah.

01:01:39.143 --> 01:01:41.043
- You're going to get the
same dilation of the pupils.

01:01:42.870 --> 01:01:43.703
And I'm always reminding people

01:01:43.703 --> 01:01:45.930
that these two little goodies
are two pieces of brain,

01:01:45.930 --> 01:01:46.763
basically,
[Karl chuckles]

01:01:46.763 --> 01:01:47.960
they're just outside the cranial vault.

01:01:47.960 --> 01:01:49.820
So they're not unlike
the vagus in that sense,

01:01:49.820 --> 01:01:52.360
but they're more of a
report than a control knob,

01:01:52.360 --> 01:01:54.750
although I'd like to
think they could be used

01:01:54.750 --> 01:01:55.863
as control knobs too.

01:01:58.220 --> 01:01:59.630
So, without putting you on the spot,

01:01:59.630 --> 01:02:00.997
again, to diagnose me,
[Karl laughs]

01:02:00.997 --> 01:02:03.089
that's something I would
never ask you to do

01:02:03.089 --> 01:02:04.580
[Karl laughing]
with the cameras rolling,

01:02:04.580 --> 01:02:07.000
but what are you looking for

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:09.200
that the patient might not be aware of?

01:02:09.200 --> 01:02:12.600
In other words, can you see
depression in somebody's eyes?

01:02:12.600 --> 01:02:15.250
And if you know a patient or if you don't,

01:02:15.250 --> 01:02:19.173
can you see it in their body
posture when they walk in?

01:02:20.010 --> 01:02:22.410
Realizing of course, that
a trained psychiatrist

01:02:22.410 --> 01:02:25.310
like yourself, develops an intuitive sense

01:02:25.310 --> 01:02:29.060
that's aggregating lots of
different features of a patient,

01:02:29.060 --> 01:02:30.280
but what about the eyes?

01:02:30.280 --> 01:02:31.330
What's going on there?

01:02:31.330 --> 01:02:32.163
- Yeah.

01:02:32.163 --> 01:02:34.620
The eyes are incredibly
rich in information.

01:02:34.620 --> 01:02:37.600
And as you alluded to though,

01:02:37.600 --> 01:02:40.930
it's not as if any one measurable

01:02:40.930 --> 01:02:42.480
conveys all the information you need.

01:02:42.480 --> 01:02:46.241
It's what an engineer would
say, joint statistics.

01:02:46.241 --> 01:02:49.040
It's many things all at once,

01:02:49.040 --> 01:02:51.730
whether they're in synchrony
or out of synchrony,

01:02:51.730 --> 01:02:54.740
that actually turns out to matter.

01:02:54.740 --> 01:02:58.010
And the eye contact question,

01:02:58.010 --> 01:03:00.160
we all know eye contact
is incredibly important.

01:03:00.160 --> 01:03:02.650
You don't feel you've
connected with somebody,

01:03:02.650 --> 01:03:06.473
unless there's eye contact, but
eye contact can go awry too.

01:03:08.039 --> 01:03:09.790
It can be too intense,

01:03:09.790 --> 01:03:14.790
or it can be mistimed, or if
there's someone with autism,

01:03:15.580 --> 01:03:17.330
it can be barely there at all.

01:03:17.330 --> 01:03:21.220
And this is one of the most
striking symptoms of autism,

01:03:21.220 --> 01:03:24.103
is the avoidance of eye contact,

01:03:28.580 --> 01:03:31.940
almost as if it's a harmful quantity.

01:03:31.940 --> 01:03:34.830
And so there's an immense
amount of information

01:03:34.830 --> 01:03:36.470
you get from the eyes,

01:03:36.470 --> 01:03:40.420
but it's the pairing of
what's going on in the eyes,

01:03:40.420 --> 01:03:43.210
with everything else going
on, the body language,

01:03:43.210 --> 01:03:46.940
the verbal content of what's coming out.

01:03:46.940 --> 01:03:50.608
All that together is the art of psychiatry

01:03:50.608 --> 01:03:53.210
and social interaction.

01:03:53.210 --> 01:03:55.170
But sometimes you don't
have the eye contact.

01:03:55.170 --> 01:03:56.310
And this is an amazing thing

01:03:56.310 --> 01:03:58.170
and I do talk about this
in the book as well.

01:03:58.170 --> 01:04:01.670
In many cases in psychiatry,
sometimes it's over the phone

01:04:01.670 --> 01:04:04.150
that you have to make key decisions.

01:04:04.150 --> 01:04:09.150
And as I recall, vividly
being as a resident,

01:04:10.080 --> 01:04:12.770
very often you have to
take these phone calls

01:04:12.770 --> 01:04:17.100
from people who are not in the hospital,

01:04:17.100 --> 01:04:19.327
people you can't see,
you can't see their eyes,

01:04:19.327 --> 01:04:21.710
you can't see their body
or anything about them,

01:04:21.710 --> 01:04:23.240
just the sound of their voice.

01:04:23.240 --> 01:04:24.750
And you can ask them questions,

01:04:24.750 --> 01:04:27.140
and you have to make, in some cases,

01:04:27.140 --> 01:04:28.530
life or death decisions.

01:04:28.530 --> 01:04:31.770
Is this person truly suicidal?

01:04:31.770 --> 01:04:34.220
Something like that, as
it comes up all the time.

01:04:35.170 --> 01:04:37.933
And so I developed over
the course of training,

01:04:39.489 --> 01:04:41.890
and I think all psychiatrists do this,

01:04:41.890 --> 01:04:45.020
is you develop a way that
data stream you have,

01:04:45.020 --> 01:04:47.550
whether it's the eyes or
whether it's just the sound

01:04:47.550 --> 01:04:49.570
of a voice coming over the phone,

01:04:49.570 --> 01:04:51.760
you learn to hone in on
that data stream you have

01:04:51.760 --> 01:04:56.211
and focus on it and identify changes

01:04:56.211 --> 01:04:58.620
and it's quite amazing.

01:04:58.620 --> 01:05:01.630
I found that you can actually...

01:05:01.630 --> 01:05:05.290
If you know a patient, you can
detect very precise changes

01:05:05.290 --> 01:05:07.220
in mood, just from the sound of the voice.

01:05:07.220 --> 01:05:11.030
And you can have a realization

01:05:11.030 --> 01:05:13.420
that oh, this patient's
depression has improved

01:05:14.620 --> 01:05:18.630
by about half, just by
the tone of their voice.

01:05:18.630 --> 01:05:21.440
And same with eyes, with enough practice,

01:05:21.440 --> 01:05:24.810
you can get enough information
from a single data stream

01:05:24.810 --> 01:05:26.430
to give you some information,

01:05:26.430 --> 01:05:27.440
but when you do have the whole picture

01:05:27.440 --> 01:05:29.900
of that, of course, is best.

01:05:29.900 --> 01:05:34.900
- So, so many theories out
there about excessive blinking

01:05:35.010 --> 01:05:38.133
and lying, lack of
blinking and sociopathy.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:40.080
I like to remind people

01:05:40.080 --> 01:05:43.666
that people have varying degrees
of lubrication of the eyes,

01:05:43.666 --> 01:05:44.590
[Karl laughs]
which also influence

01:05:44.590 --> 01:05:47.330
the frequency of blinking and
presumably have nothing to do

01:05:47.330 --> 01:05:50.650
with whether or not what
they're saying is true or not.

01:05:50.650 --> 01:05:54.150
But incredible, nonetheless,
that the eyes are a portal

01:05:54.150 --> 01:05:56.560
to overall arousal state.

01:05:56.560 --> 01:05:59.060
I'm fascinated by the effects
of light on circadian biology

01:05:59.060 --> 01:06:02.633
and just overall desire to be
awake or asleep, et cetera.

01:06:04.190 --> 01:06:06.480
So the eyes are on the
outside of the cranial vault.

01:06:06.480 --> 01:06:10.863
The vagus is outside the
cranial vault, obviously.

01:06:11.770 --> 01:06:14.563
What about the goodies in here?

01:06:15.650 --> 01:06:19.090
Parkinson's, we know at
least one of the major sites

01:06:19.090 --> 01:06:22.363
of degeneration and failure
that lead to those symptoms.

01:06:24.170 --> 01:06:25.900
I can name off any number of other things.

01:06:25.900 --> 01:06:27.810
In your book, you talk about
the beautiful work done

01:06:27.810 --> 01:06:30.570
with optogenetics of active
versus passive coping,

01:06:30.570 --> 01:06:32.380
that there are areas of
the brain like the habenula

01:06:32.380 --> 01:06:36.430
that when active, make
animals and presumably people,

01:06:36.430 --> 01:06:40.930
passive and unwilling, or
uninterested in fighting back

01:06:40.930 --> 01:06:44.320
against pressures of life,
whereas another region,

01:06:44.320 --> 01:06:48.040
the raphe, you stimulate
that, and they actively cope.

01:06:48.040 --> 01:06:49.560
They get their grit going,

01:06:49.560 --> 01:06:51.910
and they are able to lean into life.

01:06:51.910 --> 01:06:56.910
So, how does one get to those
structures in a focused way?

01:06:57.580 --> 01:07:02.580
And what does the next two to
five, to 10 years look like?

01:07:03.520 --> 01:07:05.460
- Well, this is the promise on that,

01:07:05.460 --> 01:07:08.260
and it is on a timescale

01:07:08.260 --> 01:07:10.823
that I think things may start to play out.

01:07:12.520 --> 01:07:16.560
The specificity of optogenetics
is really only useful

01:07:16.560 --> 01:07:20.500
if you have some idea of
how to use that specificity.

01:07:20.500 --> 01:07:24.760
And actually, it's a
frustrating aspect of psychiatry

01:07:24.760 --> 01:07:28.960
that in many cases, the most
effective treatments we have,

01:07:28.960 --> 01:07:30.970
have the least specificity,

01:07:30.970 --> 01:07:33.330
electroconvulsive therapy
being a great example,

01:07:33.330 --> 01:07:34.920
where you're causing a brainwide-

01:07:34.920 --> 01:07:37.710
- Which looks barbaric, but
as you mentioned is effective.

01:07:37.710 --> 01:07:39.050
- I mean, it is.

01:07:39.050 --> 01:07:41.680
These days, it's much
more clinically safe-

01:07:41.680 --> 01:07:43.803
- It doesn't look like one
fluid there last seen in the lab

01:07:43.803 --> 01:07:45.300
[indistinct]
- No it doesn't.

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:48.183
Now it's a very clinically
safe and stable procedure,

01:07:49.377 --> 01:07:51.503
but I would say yeah,

01:07:51.503 --> 01:07:56.270
it's got this almost
medieval lack of specificity,

01:07:56.270 --> 01:07:59.210
even if the procedure is
well-controlled and clinically safe

01:07:59.210 --> 01:08:02.740
and stable, and it's not very specific.

01:08:02.740 --> 01:08:04.270
You're causing a brainwide seizure.

01:08:04.270 --> 01:08:06.260
How could you be less specific than that?

01:08:06.260 --> 01:08:09.020
- And we don't know the
source of the relief.

01:08:09.020 --> 01:08:09.894
- [Karl] We don't know-

01:08:09.894 --> 01:08:11.350
- Presumably it's a
dump of neuromodulators

01:08:11.350 --> 01:08:13.541
like dopamine and serotonin,
but we don't really know-

01:08:13.541 --> 01:08:14.910
- There certainly is a
dump of neuromodulators.

01:08:14.910 --> 01:08:18.210
We don't know that that's
the cause for the relief.

01:08:18.210 --> 01:08:20.240
And likewise with medications,

01:08:20.240 --> 01:08:22.290
this is an awesome and interesting thing.

01:08:23.530 --> 01:08:26.170
Some of the most
effective antidepressants,

01:08:26.170 --> 01:08:28.240
some of the most effective anti-psychotics

01:08:28.240 --> 01:08:30.740
are the ones that have
the most side effects

01:08:30.740 --> 01:08:32.560
and there are many examples of this.

01:08:32.560 --> 01:08:35.200
For example, the most
effective anti-psychotic

01:08:35.200 --> 01:08:36.700
is something called clozapine,

01:08:38.242 --> 01:08:39.790
which unquestionably has
the most side effects.

01:08:39.790 --> 01:08:40.887
It has terrible, terrible side effects.

01:08:40.887 --> 01:08:42.360
- The D4 antagonist?

01:08:42.360 --> 01:08:44.880
- It has basically
every receptor. [laughs]

01:08:44.880 --> 01:08:45.713
- Does it really?

01:08:45.713 --> 01:08:46.860
- Yeah.
- Interesting.

01:08:46.860 --> 01:08:51.040
- Yeah, it has prominent
serotonin, prominent muscarinic,

01:08:51.040 --> 01:08:52.880
certainly acts on dopamine receptors,

01:08:52.880 --> 01:08:57.880
but it causes blood cell
counts change- [laughs]

01:08:58.047 --> 01:08:59.400
- How do people feel?

01:08:59.400 --> 01:09:02.070
So if I were schizophrenic

01:09:02.070 --> 01:09:05.240
and I was getting auditory
hallucinations, et cetera,

01:09:05.240 --> 01:09:10.240
and I took clozapine, what
could I expect to feel?

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:13.570
- Well, so you would notice side effects,

01:09:13.570 --> 01:09:16.550
and you would notice resolution
of symptoms both and-

01:09:16.550 --> 01:09:17.870
- So the voices would go away?

01:09:17.870 --> 01:09:18.703
- Yeah.

01:09:18.703 --> 01:09:19.674
- But in a good situation,

01:09:19.674 --> 01:09:21.430
the voices would go away?
- That's right.

01:09:21.430 --> 01:09:23.720
- But I would feel not good in my body?

01:09:23.720 --> 01:09:26.290
- You might have dizziness,

01:09:26.290 --> 01:09:31.040
you might have drooling,
you might have any number

01:09:31.040 --> 01:09:36.040
of physical sensations
that would be due to these

01:09:37.080 --> 01:09:39.390
off target effects, the medication acting

01:09:39.390 --> 01:09:40.670
on these other receptors-

01:09:40.670 --> 01:09:41.820
- I'm certainly not suggesting this,

01:09:41.820 --> 01:09:45.180
but what if somebody without
schizophrenia took clozapine?

01:09:45.180 --> 01:09:47.432
- They'd have the same side
effects presumably, yeah.

01:09:47.432 --> 01:09:50.621
And so it would not be something
that I would recommend.

01:09:50.621 --> 01:09:51.454
- Yeah.

01:09:51.454 --> 01:09:53.160
Do psychiatrists take the
drugs that they prescribe?

01:09:53.160 --> 01:09:53.993
[Karl laughs]

01:09:53.993 --> 01:09:55.760
I just finished for the third time,

01:09:55.760 --> 01:09:59.333
Oliver Sacks' autobiography
which is marvelous

01:09:59.333 --> 01:10:02.120
and I highly recommend to people.

01:10:02.120 --> 01:10:03.873
He certainly took a lot of drugs,

01:10:05.030 --> 01:10:07.163
not as part of his professional role,

01:10:08.070 --> 01:10:11.700
but just out of curiosity,
what is the interest

01:10:11.700 --> 01:10:15.000
or kind of role of drugs
in the field of psychiatry?

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:16.610
Because I would imagine for a group

01:10:16.610 --> 01:10:19.200
of very curious introspective people

01:10:19.200 --> 01:10:21.650
who are making recommendations
about what to take,

01:10:21.650 --> 01:10:24.280
there could actually be some
benefit for understanding

01:10:24.280 --> 01:10:26.490
what the experience of
those drugs was like

01:10:26.490 --> 01:10:27.370
for their patients.

01:10:27.370 --> 01:10:29.017
- I think that's true.

01:10:29.017 --> 01:10:32.240
And I will say that probably
many or most psychiatrists

01:10:32.240 --> 01:10:36.430
have sampled the number of
these for exactly the reason

01:10:36.430 --> 01:10:38.560
that you're saying is to understand better

01:10:38.560 --> 01:10:41.305
and to help treat their patients better.

01:10:41.305 --> 01:10:42.555
And I've spoken to people

01:10:45.954 --> 01:10:47.060
who have found this very helpful to know,

01:10:47.060 --> 01:10:50.350
okay, this sleep disruption
caused by this medication

01:10:50.350 --> 01:10:53.270
or the libido disruption caused
by this other medication.

01:10:53.270 --> 01:10:55.126
Wow, that is a big effect.

01:10:55.126 --> 01:10:57.680
And it really helps with empathy

01:10:57.680 --> 01:10:59.514
for the patients to understand.

01:10:59.514 --> 01:11:03.250
- I'm not suggesting that
physicians or anybody

01:11:04.530 --> 01:11:07.480
experiment with drugs, but
I am relieved to hear that,

01:11:07.480 --> 01:11:08.820
because I think that when you're talking

01:11:08.820 --> 01:11:12.580
about accessing somebody's mind
and their basic physiology,

01:11:12.580 --> 01:11:15.540
as you've mentioned, relate
to appetite, libido and sleep,

01:11:15.540 --> 01:11:18.740
really, one is acting as a mechanic

01:11:18.740 --> 01:11:20.830
of the person's whole experience.

01:11:20.830 --> 01:11:24.360
They walk out of the office
and they have a life experience

01:11:24.360 --> 01:11:25.880
that extends beyond the script.

01:11:25.880 --> 01:11:27.060
- Yeah.

01:11:27.060 --> 01:11:30.420
And so at the same time though,

01:11:30.420 --> 01:11:32.780
you can't let that completely
guide your clinical decisions,

01:11:32.780 --> 01:11:35.360
because as I mentioned,
some of these medications

01:11:35.360 --> 01:11:36.470
that have the most side effects,

01:11:36.470 --> 01:11:38.200
they are also the most effective

01:11:38.200 --> 01:11:39.620
and clozapine is a great example.

01:11:39.620 --> 01:11:42.510
That will work in patients
where nothing else works.

01:11:42.510 --> 01:11:44.590
And believe me, we don't take the step

01:11:44.590 --> 01:11:46.810
of clozapine prescription lightly,

01:11:46.810 --> 01:11:48.310
because of all these side effects.

01:11:48.310 --> 01:11:50.680
You have to come in for
a weekly blood cell,

01:11:50.680 --> 01:11:52.470
or every few weeks of blood cell check,

01:11:52.470 --> 01:11:55.820
to make sure that the blood
counts are not off for example,

01:11:55.820 --> 01:11:58.620
but there are patients where
no other medication works

01:11:58.620 --> 01:12:00.734
for the schizophrenia and
clozapine works amazingly well-

01:12:00.734 --> 01:12:01.767
- That's marvelous.

01:12:01.767 --> 01:12:05.320
- And so we do it, even though
there are the side effects.

01:12:05.320 --> 01:12:07.340
And so then this comes
back to your question,

01:12:07.340 --> 01:12:09.860
what if we had better
and better specificity?

01:12:09.860 --> 01:12:12.757
Well, only if we know exactly
what we're doing is the point.

01:12:12.757 --> 01:12:15.920
And so because as we become more refined,

01:12:15.920 --> 01:12:19.280
we'd better be right about
where we we're refining to..

01:12:19.280 --> 01:12:21.050
- And do you imagine
a day where it will be

01:12:21.050 --> 01:12:24.320
a single, maybe even
outpatient neurosurgery,

01:12:24.320 --> 01:12:26.400
would go in through the
skull or the back of the ear,

01:12:26.400 --> 01:12:27.607
deliver a small viral injection

01:12:27.607 --> 01:12:29.580
of one of these adenoviruses,

01:12:29.580 --> 01:12:32.683
a little sticker of light-emitting diode,

01:12:33.670 --> 01:12:36.610
deep in the brain, is that
how you envision this someday?

01:12:36.610 --> 01:12:37.720
- That certainly could happen.

01:12:37.720 --> 01:12:42.720
What I actually prefer as a
vision is still medications,

01:12:43.960 --> 01:12:48.760
because those are minimally invasive.

01:12:48.760 --> 01:12:49.890
If we knew what we were doing,

01:12:49.890 --> 01:12:53.970
we could make them more specific,
have fewer side effects,

01:12:53.970 --> 01:12:56.130
but optogenetics, that will arm us

01:12:56.130 --> 01:12:58.060
with true causal understanding.

01:12:58.060 --> 01:13:00.020
And so we'll know,

01:13:00.020 --> 01:13:02.480
and we're already moving
rapidly toward this point,

01:13:02.480 --> 01:13:04.563
we'll know okay, this symptom,

01:13:05.510 --> 01:13:08.300
loss of pleasure in life
that we call anhedonia,

01:13:08.300 --> 01:13:12.220
or the loss of motivation or energy

01:13:12.220 --> 01:13:14.413
to overcome challenges, active coping,

01:13:15.360 --> 01:13:19.540
these are largely subserved,
largely controlled

01:13:19.540 --> 01:13:22.033
by this circuit or that
circuit or the cell

01:13:22.033 --> 01:13:24.210
that inhabits this other circuit.

01:13:24.210 --> 01:13:26.630
- And we will know that
because of the work done

01:13:26.630 --> 01:13:27.463
with channelopsins?

01:13:27.463 --> 01:13:28.780
- Exactly.
- Yeah. I agree.

01:13:28.780 --> 01:13:32.300
- In ways that we never could
have the confidence otherwise.

01:13:32.300 --> 01:13:34.304
And so we'll know that this is the circuit

01:13:34.304 --> 01:13:38.610
that underlies the
symptom or its resolution.

01:13:38.610 --> 01:13:42.950
And then we'll get to understand
these cells very deeply,

01:13:42.950 --> 01:13:46.560
okay, these cells that are
causal, that do matter,

01:13:46.560 --> 01:13:48.860
who are they? What's their wiring?

01:13:48.860 --> 01:13:51.170
What are the proteins that they make?

01:13:51.170 --> 01:13:54.070
What are the little things
that are on the surface

01:13:54.070 --> 01:13:57.620
of the cell that could be
receptors for specific medications

01:13:57.620 --> 01:14:00.330
or combinations of receptors

01:14:00.330 --> 01:14:02.870
that would give us the
specificity we need?

01:14:02.870 --> 01:14:06.590
And then, armed with
that causal and precise

01:14:06.590 --> 01:14:09.020
and rigorous knowledge,
then you can imagine

01:14:09.020 --> 01:14:11.050
medication development
becoming totally different,

01:14:11.050 --> 01:14:15.410
no longer serendipitous, but
truly grounded in causality.

01:14:15.410 --> 01:14:16.243
- I see.

01:14:16.243 --> 01:14:19.190
So using channelopsins as a
way to probe the circuitry

01:14:19.190 --> 01:14:22.970
and figure out the sites
that are disrupted,

01:14:22.970 --> 01:14:24.910
what patterns of activity are required?

01:14:24.910 --> 01:14:28.390
And then, by understanding the
constituents of those cells,

01:14:28.390 --> 01:14:30.040
like what they express and what they make,

01:14:30.040 --> 01:14:32.860
then developing drugs that
could target those cells,

01:14:32.860 --> 01:14:35.310
not necessarily putting
light-inducing diodes

01:14:35.310 --> 01:14:38.200
into the brain, or walking
around with wire packs

01:14:38.200 --> 01:14:39.886
attached to our skull
or something like that.

01:14:39.886 --> 01:14:40.890
- [Karl] Right. Exactly.

01:14:40.890 --> 01:14:42.350
- That's fantastic.

01:14:42.350 --> 01:14:46.450
And I realized no one has a crystal ball,

01:14:46.450 --> 01:14:50.350
but what do you think the arc of that is?

01:14:50.350 --> 01:14:53.030
Meaning, are we going
to see that in a year?

01:14:53.030 --> 01:14:55.410
In two years? Three years?

01:14:55.410 --> 01:14:56.423
Let me reframe that.

01:14:57.490 --> 01:15:00.870
How soon will a pill-based treatment

01:15:00.870 --> 01:15:03.100
for a psychiatric disease be available,

01:15:03.100 --> 01:15:06.370
that targets a specific set of cells

01:15:06.370 --> 01:15:10.200
that we know are important
because of the work done

01:15:10.200 --> 01:15:11.950
with channelopsins?

01:15:11.950 --> 01:15:16.950
- I think that in some
ways it's already happening

01:15:16.950 --> 01:15:19.123
at the level of individual patients-

01:15:20.045 --> 01:15:21.010
- Here at Stanford?

01:15:21.010 --> 01:15:22.614
- Yeah. Yup.

01:15:22.614 --> 01:15:26.490
And more broadly in terms of new drugs,

01:15:26.490 --> 01:15:30.640
new multi-centered clinical
trials that will play out

01:15:30.640 --> 01:15:32.203
over the next few years.

01:15:33.160 --> 01:15:36.320
And these could be drugs
that are already safe

01:15:36.320 --> 01:15:39.420
and approved for other purposes,

01:15:39.420 --> 01:15:41.830
but we might say okay, now we know

01:15:41.830 --> 01:15:45.950
that this medication,
based on what we know

01:15:45.950 --> 01:15:49.230
from causal optogenetics,
this could be useful

01:15:49.230 --> 01:15:52.740
for this other purpose,
this psychiatric symptom.

01:15:52.740 --> 01:15:56.530
And so the path to helping patients

01:15:56.530 --> 01:15:59.020
could be relatively swift.

01:15:59.020 --> 01:16:00.750
- That's very exciting.

01:16:00.750 --> 01:16:03.920
What are your thoughts about
brain machine interface

01:16:03.920 --> 01:16:06.760
and Neuralink always comes up,

01:16:06.760 --> 01:16:09.690
although I do want to point
out a tremendous respect

01:16:09.690 --> 01:16:10.780
for the folks at Neuralink

01:16:10.780 --> 01:16:12.530
including someone who
came up through my lab,

01:16:12.530 --> 01:16:13.730
is now there as a neurosurgeon,

01:16:13.730 --> 01:16:16.970
but the brain machine
interface is something

01:16:16.970 --> 01:16:19.210
that's been happening for a long time now,

01:16:19.210 --> 01:16:22.580
some of the best work, among
the best work being done here

01:16:22.580 --> 01:16:25.750
at Stanford and elsewhere too of course,

01:16:25.750 --> 01:16:28.020
is what you just described compatible with

01:16:28.020 --> 01:16:29.770
or different than brain machine interface,

01:16:29.770 --> 01:16:32.560
meaning devices, little
probes are going to stimulate

01:16:32.560 --> 01:16:35.440
different patterns of activity
and ensembles of neurons?

01:16:35.440 --> 01:16:36.730
And what are your general thoughts

01:16:36.730 --> 01:16:40.233
about brain machine
interfaces going forward?

01:16:41.250 --> 01:16:43.379
- I mean, first of all,

01:16:43.379 --> 01:16:47.280
it's an amazing scientific
discovery approach,

01:16:47.280 --> 01:16:49.410
as you mentioned, we and
others here at Stanford

01:16:49.410 --> 01:16:52.180
are using electrodes,
collecting information

01:16:52.180 --> 01:16:54.530
from tens of thousands of neurons-

01:16:54.530 --> 01:16:56.380
- In humans, I should
add. Yeah. [chuckles]

01:16:56.380 --> 01:17:00.360
- And even, yes, it is quite even separate

01:17:00.360 --> 01:17:02.170
from the Neuralink work as you point out,

01:17:02.170 --> 01:17:05.150
many people have been
doing this in humans,

01:17:05.150 --> 01:17:06.823
as well as in non-human primates.

01:17:07.810 --> 01:17:10.840
And this is pretty
powerful, it's important.

01:17:10.840 --> 01:17:13.740
This will let us understand
what's going on in the brain,

01:17:13.740 --> 01:17:18.180
in psychiatric disease
and neurological disease,

01:17:18.180 --> 01:17:20.133
and will give us ideas for treatment.

01:17:21.900 --> 01:17:24.527
It is, of course still invasive.

01:17:24.527 --> 01:17:29.527
You still are talking about
putting a device into the brain.

01:17:30.130 --> 01:17:34.210
And that has to be treated

01:17:34.210 --> 01:17:36.810
as a situation that has some risks,

01:17:36.810 --> 01:17:39.403
and a step that has to be taken carefully.

01:17:40.630 --> 01:17:42.270
I see that as something

01:17:42.270 --> 01:17:47.270
that will be part of
psychiatry in the long run,

01:17:47.970 --> 01:17:51.050
already with deep brain
stimulation approaches,

01:17:51.050 --> 01:17:54.680
we can help people with
psychiatric disorders.

01:17:54.680 --> 01:17:56.560
And that's putting just
a single electrode,

01:17:56.560 --> 01:18:00.310
not even a complex closed loop system

01:18:00.310 --> 01:18:02.830
where you're both playing in
and getting information back,

01:18:02.830 --> 01:18:06.000
even just a single stimulation
electrode in the brain

01:18:06.000 --> 01:18:10.063
can help people with OCD, for
example, quite powerfully.

01:18:11.240 --> 01:18:12.710
And that will become much more powerful

01:18:12.710 --> 01:18:15.010
when we get to a true
brain machine interface,

01:18:15.010 --> 01:18:17.370
collecting information back,

01:18:17.370 --> 01:18:18.940
stimulating only when you need to.

01:18:18.940 --> 01:18:23.340
If we could identify a
pathological activity pattern,

01:18:23.340 --> 01:18:25.670
a particular, almost like the prodrome

01:18:25.670 --> 01:18:27.140
or the early stage of a seizure,

01:18:27.140 --> 01:18:30.340
maybe there are events
that happened leading up to

01:18:30.340 --> 01:18:34.213
on some timescale, a psychiatric symptom

01:18:34.213 --> 01:18:37.300
that we could intervene
in a closed loop way

01:18:37.300 --> 01:18:40.260
to detect what's happening,
what's starting to go wrong,

01:18:40.260 --> 01:18:43.310
feed that back to the brain
stimulation electrode,

01:18:43.310 --> 01:18:46.613
have it be in that way more
efficient and more principled.

01:18:49.210 --> 01:18:50.370
I think it's great.

01:18:50.370 --> 01:18:53.450
It's something that of
course will be grounded again

01:18:53.450 --> 01:18:55.130
and causal understanding,
we'll need to know,

01:18:55.130 --> 01:18:57.640
what is that pathological
pattern that we're detecting?

01:18:57.640 --> 01:18:59.050
And we need to know that it matters.

01:18:59.050 --> 01:19:00.933
And so again, that's where
optogenetics is helping us.

01:19:00.933 --> 01:19:04.210
It's helping us know, okay,
this pattern of activity

01:19:04.210 --> 01:19:07.840
in these cells and these
circuits, this does mean

01:19:07.840 --> 01:19:11.123
that there's a particular kind
of symptom that's happening.

01:19:12.220 --> 01:19:13.991
But armed with that knowledge, absolutely,

01:19:13.991 --> 01:19:17.600
even the simple closed loop
device detect and stimulate

01:19:17.600 --> 01:19:19.352
is going to be part of
psychiatry in the future.

01:19:19.352 --> 01:19:22.640
And then of course, as
you get to more cells,

01:19:22.640 --> 01:19:25.830
more connections, the ability
that we have to help people

01:19:25.830 --> 01:19:27.130
will become more powerful.

01:19:28.060 --> 01:19:32.160
- One of the questions I get
asked a lot is about ADHD

01:19:32.160 --> 01:19:35.020
and attention deficit of various kinds.

01:19:35.020 --> 01:19:39.210
I have a hunch, that one
reason I get asked so often

01:19:39.210 --> 01:19:44.010
is that people are feeling
really distracted and challenged

01:19:44.010 --> 01:19:47.023
in funneling their attention
and their behavior.

01:19:49.501 --> 01:19:51.250
And there are number of
reasons for that, of course,

01:19:51.250 --> 01:19:56.250
but what is true ADHD, and
what does it look like?

01:19:56.520 --> 01:19:58.020
What can be done for it?

01:19:58.020 --> 01:20:01.390
And what if any role for channelopsins

01:20:01.390 --> 01:20:04.750
or these downstream technologies
that you're developing,

01:20:04.750 --> 01:20:08.470
what do they offer for
people that suffer from ADHD

01:20:08.470 --> 01:20:11.493
or have a family member
that suffers from ADHD?

01:20:12.610 --> 01:20:16.333
- This is a pretty interesting
branch of psychiatry.

01:20:16.333 --> 01:20:18.660
There's no question that
people have been helped

01:20:18.660 --> 01:20:22.640
by the treatments, there's active debate

01:20:22.640 --> 01:20:27.640
over what fraction of people
who have these symptoms

01:20:27.690 --> 01:20:29.860
can or should be treated?

01:20:29.860 --> 01:20:32.350
- This is typically Adderall
or stimulants of some kind?

01:20:32.350 --> 01:20:34.710
- Yeah, for example the
stimulants, that's right.

01:20:34.710 --> 01:20:39.490
So ADHD as its name
suggests, it has symptoms of,

01:20:39.490 --> 01:20:41.910
it can have either a hyperactive state

01:20:41.910 --> 01:20:44.410
or an inattentive state,

01:20:44.410 --> 01:20:48.070
and those can be completely
separate from each other.

01:20:48.070 --> 01:20:51.720
You could have a patient who effectively

01:20:51.720 --> 01:20:55.050
is not hyperactive at all,
but can remain focused

01:20:55.050 --> 01:20:57.080
on what's going on around them-

01:20:57.080 --> 01:20:58.470
- So the body can be still,

01:20:58.470 --> 01:21:00.630
but their mind is darting around?

01:21:00.630 --> 01:21:01.463
- That's right.

01:21:01.463 --> 01:21:03.340
- Or they can be very
hyperactive with their body.

01:21:03.340 --> 01:21:04.173
- Yeah, it happens both ways.

01:21:04.173 --> 01:21:06.120
- Probably rarely is somebody
hyperactive with their body

01:21:06.120 --> 01:21:07.230
but their mind is still,

01:21:07.230 --> 01:21:08.063
[Karl laughs]
although I have to say,

01:21:08.063 --> 01:21:10.820
and this is a benevolent
shout out to Botond Rosca,

01:21:10.820 --> 01:21:14.810
Botond has an incredibly
sharp and focused mind.

01:21:14.810 --> 01:21:15.643
- Yeah.

01:21:15.643 --> 01:21:16.568
- And his hand movements

01:21:16.568 --> 01:21:17.980
[Karl laughs]
are extremely exact also,

01:21:17.980 --> 01:21:20.630
so I do sometimes wonder, whether or not

01:21:20.630 --> 01:21:22.463
our body movements and our head movements,

01:21:22.463 --> 01:21:24.330
whether or not they're coordinated or not

01:21:24.330 --> 01:21:28.540
is a readout of how
directed our attention is.

01:21:28.540 --> 01:21:31.400
- I noticed, I have to think
complex, abstract thoughts.

01:21:31.400 --> 01:21:32.970
I noticed I have to be very still.

01:21:32.970 --> 01:21:36.020
So my body has to be
almost completely on moving

01:21:36.020 --> 01:21:39.620
for me to think very
abstractly and deeply.

01:21:39.620 --> 01:21:40.620
Other people are different.

01:21:40.620 --> 01:21:41.790
Some people, when they're running,

01:21:41.790 --> 01:21:42.800
they get their best thoughts.

01:21:42.800 --> 01:21:44.100
I can't even imagine that.

01:21:44.100 --> 01:21:45.880
My brain does not work that way at all.

01:21:45.880 --> 01:21:47.860
I have to be totally motionless, [laughs]

01:21:47.860 --> 01:21:48.870
which is kind of interesting.

01:21:48.870 --> 01:21:50.040
- How do you go about that?

01:21:50.040 --> 01:21:55.040
- I sit much like this, I
try to have time in each day

01:21:56.150 --> 01:22:01.150
where I'm literally sitting
almost in this position,

01:22:01.980 --> 01:22:04.210
but without distraction and thinking,

01:22:04.210 --> 01:22:07.440
and so it's almost
meditative in some ways,

01:22:07.440 --> 01:22:10.440
except it's not true meditation,

01:22:10.440 --> 01:22:13.134
but I am thinking, well, I'm not moving-

01:22:13.134 --> 01:22:15.644
- You're trying to structure
your thoughts in that time?

01:22:15.644 --> 01:22:16.477
- Yeah.

01:22:16.477 --> 01:22:17.550
- Interesting.
- Yeah.

01:22:17.550 --> 01:22:20.760
So, but everybody, as you
say is very different.

01:22:20.760 --> 01:22:24.610
And so with ADHD, the key
thing is we want to make sure

01:22:24.610 --> 01:22:28.770
that this is present across
different domains of life,

01:22:28.770 --> 01:22:31.050
school and home, to show that it really

01:22:31.050 --> 01:22:34.200
is a pervasive pattern,
and not something specific

01:22:34.200 --> 01:22:38.030
to the teacher or the home
situation or something.

01:22:38.030 --> 01:22:39.190
And then you can help patients.

01:22:39.190 --> 01:22:42.580
It's interesting that ADHD
is one of those disorders

01:22:42.580 --> 01:22:43.910
where people are trying to work

01:22:43.910 --> 01:22:46.630
on quantitative EEG-based diagnoses,

01:22:46.630 --> 01:22:48.360
and so there's some progress

01:22:48.360 --> 01:22:52.750
toward making a diagnosis
looking at particular,

01:22:52.750 --> 01:22:55.330
externally detectable brainwave rhythm-

01:22:55.330 --> 01:22:57.070
- So skullcap with some electrodes

01:22:57.070 --> 01:22:58.300
that don't penetrate the skull?

01:22:58.300 --> 01:22:59.133
- That's right.

01:22:59.133 --> 01:23:01.447
- And this can be done in
an hour or two-hour session?

01:23:01.447 --> 01:23:02.280
- Yeah, that's right.

01:23:02.280 --> 01:23:03.970
- It has to be done in a clinic, right?

01:23:03.970 --> 01:23:05.087
- Yeah, in the clinic, right,

01:23:05.087 --> 01:23:07.060
and you have to have the
right recording apparatus

01:23:07.060 --> 01:23:07.893
and so on,

01:23:10.503 --> 01:23:13.420
but in principle, increase
in confidence comes

01:23:13.420 --> 01:23:18.390
in exactly which measurements
one could even imagine

01:23:18.390 --> 01:23:21.493
moving toward home tests,
but we're not there yet.

01:23:22.460 --> 01:23:23.293
- Amazing.

01:23:23.293 --> 01:23:25.160
I think one of the reasons
I get asked about it so much

01:23:25.160 --> 01:23:28.010
is a lot of people
wonder if they have ADHD.

01:23:28.010 --> 01:23:30.860
Do you think that some
of the lifestyle factors

01:23:30.860 --> 01:23:34.510
that inhabit us all these days,

01:23:34.510 --> 01:23:38.040
could induce a subclinical
or a clinical-like ADHD?

01:23:40.390 --> 01:23:42.740
I look at people's phone
use including my own,

01:23:42.740 --> 01:23:44.500
and I don't think of it like addiction,

01:23:44.500 --> 01:23:47.130
it looks to me and feels
to me more like OCD.

01:23:47.130 --> 01:23:48.970
And I'll come clean here by
saying when I was younger,

01:23:48.970 --> 01:23:51.360
when I was a kid, I had a grunting tic.

01:23:51.360 --> 01:23:52.193
I used to hide it.

01:23:52.193 --> 01:23:53.530
I actually used to hide in the closet,

01:23:53.530 --> 01:23:55.373
'cause my dad would make me stop.

01:23:57.536 --> 01:23:59.230
And I couldn't feel any relief of my mind

01:23:59.230 --> 01:24:00.590
until I [grunts] would do this.

01:24:00.590 --> 01:24:02.950
And actually now, if I get very tired,

01:24:02.950 --> 01:24:05.153
if I've been pushing long
hours, it'll come back.

01:24:05.153 --> 01:24:05.986
- Interesting.

01:24:05.986 --> 01:24:07.003
- I was not treated for it,

01:24:08.090 --> 01:24:11.270
but I will confess that
I've had the experience

01:24:11.270 --> 01:24:14.490
of, I always liked sports where
I involved a lot of impact,

01:24:14.490 --> 01:24:16.960
fortunately not football,
because I went to a high school

01:24:16.960 --> 01:24:18.470
where the football team was terrible.

01:24:18.470 --> 01:24:20.093
Maybe that would have avoided more impact,

01:24:20.093 --> 01:24:20.926
[Karl laughs]

01:24:20.926 --> 01:24:23.010
but things like skateboarding, boxing,

01:24:23.010 --> 01:24:24.640
they bring relief.

01:24:24.640 --> 01:24:27.764
I feel clarity after a
head hit, which I avoid,

01:24:27.764 --> 01:24:28.597
[Karl laughs]

01:24:28.597 --> 01:24:30.120
but I used to say that's the only time

01:24:30.120 --> 01:24:31.740
I feel truly clear for a while.

01:24:31.740 --> 01:24:33.230
And then eventually it dissipated.

01:24:33.230 --> 01:24:35.913
By about age 16, 17, it just disappeared.

01:24:36.890 --> 01:24:40.030
So I have great empathy
for those that feel

01:24:40.030 --> 01:24:41.650
like there's something contained in them

01:24:41.650 --> 01:24:42.880
that won't allow them to focus

01:24:42.880 --> 01:24:44.620
on what they want to focus on.

01:24:44.620 --> 01:24:46.530
And these days, with the phone

01:24:46.530 --> 01:24:50.810
and all these email, et cetera, I wonder

01:24:50.810 --> 01:24:53.260
and I empathize a bit
when I hear people saying

01:24:53.260 --> 01:24:57.560
like, "I think I might have ADHD or ADD".

01:24:57.560 --> 01:25:00.250
Do you think it's possible
that our behaviors

01:25:00.250 --> 01:25:02.630
and our interaction
with the sensory world,

01:25:02.630 --> 01:25:04.950
which is really what phones
and email really are,

01:25:04.950 --> 01:25:08.744
could induce ADD or reactivate it?

01:25:08.744 --> 01:25:10.470
- This is a great question.

01:25:10.470 --> 01:25:12.530
I think about it a lot,

01:25:12.530 --> 01:25:16.610
and you mentioned this
tic-like behavior in yourself,

01:25:16.610 --> 01:25:19.330
it's very common that people who have tics

01:25:19.330 --> 01:25:21.870
have this building up of something
that can only be relieved

01:25:21.870 --> 01:25:25.380
by executing the tic which
can be a motor movement

01:25:25.380 --> 01:25:27.943
or a vocalization or even a thought.

01:25:30.900 --> 01:25:32.630
And people do, I think
these days, do have this.

01:25:32.630 --> 01:25:34.350
If they haven't checked
their phone in a while,

01:25:34.350 --> 01:25:36.190
they do have a buildup
and buildup and buildup

01:25:36.190 --> 01:25:38.918
until they can check it and relieve it.

01:25:38.918 --> 01:25:41.110
And there's some similarities,

01:25:41.110 --> 01:25:44.833
there is a little reward
that comes with the checking.

01:25:46.320 --> 01:25:48.860
But the key question in all of psychiatry,

01:25:48.860 --> 01:25:51.030
what we do is we don't diagnose something

01:25:51.030 --> 01:25:55.020
unless it's disrupting what we call social

01:25:55.020 --> 01:25:56.340
or occupational functioning.

01:25:56.340 --> 01:25:59.230
Like you could have
any number of symptoms,

