- You know, I'm always
careful to not assume

01:39:25.650 --> 01:39:27.030
we do things better.

01:39:27.030 --> 01:39:29.270
We certainly understand what we're doing

01:39:29.270 --> 01:39:31.030
better than we understand
what animals are doing,

01:39:31.030 --> 01:39:34.010
and they certainly do
things better than we do.

01:39:34.010 --> 01:39:36.850
That said, we do have
amazing, wonderful brains

01:39:36.850 --> 01:39:39.470
and many structures that
are very highly developed

01:39:39.470 --> 01:39:42.350
in our brains that are
not nearly so developed

01:39:42.350 --> 01:39:45.490
in mice and fish for example.

01:39:45.490 --> 01:39:50.029
Now, that said, when I
look at the big picture,

01:39:50.029 --> 01:39:52.913
what is the mammalian brain really doing?

01:39:54.600 --> 01:39:57.070
There are things that you
would never have thought

01:39:57.070 --> 01:40:01.933
we could study in animals and
laboratory mammals like mice,

01:40:03.958 --> 01:40:05.790
that it turns out you can, actually,

01:40:05.790 --> 01:40:07.600
and so I would never draw the line

01:40:07.600 --> 01:40:10.130
and say, here's something
you can't study in mice,

01:40:10.130 --> 01:40:12.770
or here's something that
has no parallel in mice.

01:40:12.770 --> 01:40:13.910
I would be very careful

01:40:13.910 --> 01:40:16.877
before making any statement like that.

01:40:16.877 --> 01:40:19.090
And a good example of that
is we've been able to study

01:40:19.090 --> 01:40:20.940
just in the past year,
come to an understanding

01:40:20.940 --> 01:40:24.560
of dissociation, and we had a paper

01:40:24.560 --> 01:40:28.690
that came out in late 2020,
both mouse and human work,

01:40:28.690 --> 01:40:32.440
in which we got to the
sort of the circuit basis

01:40:32.440 --> 01:40:34.140
for dissociation.

01:40:34.140 --> 01:40:35.590
Now, what is dissociation?

01:40:35.590 --> 01:40:38.810
A lot of people might
not have experienced it,

01:40:38.810 --> 01:40:40.510
but it's actually very common.

01:40:40.510 --> 01:40:44.290
More than 70% of people
who've been through trauma

01:40:44.290 --> 01:40:45.850
experience dissociation,

01:40:45.850 --> 01:40:49.730
it shows up in borderline
personality, it shows up in PTSD.

01:40:49.730 --> 01:40:53.600
What it is, is a separation
of the sense of self,

01:40:53.600 --> 01:40:55.110
from the body.

01:40:55.110 --> 01:40:57.370
So you can have someone who,
it's not as if you're numb,

01:40:57.370 --> 01:40:58.540
you're not anesthetized.

01:40:58.540 --> 01:41:02.020
You can still know that
something's happening to the body,

01:41:02.020 --> 01:41:03.300
but you just don't care,

01:41:03.300 --> 01:41:06.020
because you don't ascribe it to yourself,

01:41:06.020 --> 01:41:08.140
which is very interesting, right?

01:41:08.140 --> 01:41:09.110
How interesting is that?

01:41:09.110 --> 01:41:10.470
- The cells report narrative.

01:41:10.470 --> 01:41:11.710
- Yeah. Yeah.

01:41:11.710 --> 01:41:13.610
- In your book, you touch on this.

01:41:13.610 --> 01:41:17.110
And I will say is the most precise,

01:41:17.110 --> 01:41:19.890
and meaningful and eloquent description

01:41:19.890 --> 01:41:21.780
of what might be consciousness,

01:41:21.780 --> 01:41:25.330
this narrative toward
the self or of the self,

01:41:25.330 --> 01:41:26.430
and where it might reside.

01:41:26.430 --> 01:41:28.683
So in dissociative conditions,

01:41:29.520 --> 01:41:32.800
people are feeling as kind
of an absence of a merge

01:41:32.800 --> 01:41:34.230
between mind and body.
- Right.

01:41:34.230 --> 01:41:35.063
- Is that one way to describe it?

01:41:35.063 --> 01:41:36.050
- That's right.
- And as I recall,

01:41:36.050 --> 01:41:39.350
this paper involved an
exploration of ketamine.

01:41:39.350 --> 01:41:40.400
- Ketamine was a big part of it.

01:41:40.400 --> 01:41:41.233
Yeah, that's right.

01:41:41.233 --> 01:41:43.050
And so ketamine is
another one of those cases

01:41:43.050 --> 01:41:45.700
where people can experience dissociation.

01:41:45.700 --> 01:41:48.920
Ketamine or PCP, we call
these the dissociative drugs.

01:41:48.920 --> 01:41:52.880
They cause it just like these
other psychiatric conditions

01:41:52.880 --> 01:41:53.713
can cause it.

01:41:54.670 --> 01:41:59.370
But we were able to manifest this in mice,

01:41:59.370 --> 01:42:02.130
administering these
dissociative agents in mice.

01:42:02.130 --> 01:42:04.620
We could make them still
able to detect stimulus,

01:42:04.620 --> 01:42:07.180
but not care that it was happening.

01:42:07.180 --> 01:42:10.540
All the while we were recording

01:42:10.540 --> 01:42:12.780
the activity of individual
cells in the brain

01:42:12.780 --> 01:42:14.716
to see what was going on,

01:42:14.716 --> 01:42:18.120
what was happening along
with this dissociation,

01:42:18.120 --> 01:42:20.570
and then use optogenetics
to see that it mattered

01:42:20.570 --> 01:42:23.410
to actually provide
that pattern of activity

01:42:23.410 --> 01:42:26.620
and see, oh, that actually
causes the dissociation.

01:42:26.620 --> 01:42:28.930
So we could do all that in mice,

01:42:28.930 --> 01:42:33.840
which who would've thought
that you could study something

01:42:33.840 --> 01:42:34.700
like this in mice?

01:42:34.700 --> 01:42:38.380
And we were able to go back
and forth with human work

01:42:38.380 --> 01:42:41.970
because here in our Stanford
Comprehensive Epilepsy Center,

01:42:41.970 --> 01:42:45.330
there's a lot of what we
call Stereo EEG Recording.

01:42:45.330 --> 01:42:46.210
Patients who come in

01:42:46.210 --> 01:42:48.630
and in the course of normal clinical care,

01:42:48.630 --> 01:42:51.570
they have electrodes
recording in their brain

01:42:51.570 --> 01:42:53.440
to identify where the seizure is,

01:42:53.440 --> 01:42:57.350
so they can be candidates
for removing a little patch

01:42:57.350 --> 01:42:58.730
of the brain that's causing the seizure.

01:42:58.730 --> 01:43:01.530
This has done for patients who
medications are not helping

01:43:01.530 --> 01:43:03.600
their seizure disorder.

01:43:03.600 --> 01:43:08.200
And there was a patient who
had a dissociative state

01:43:08.200 --> 01:43:10.107
before every seizure, so
this was a human being

01:43:10.107 --> 01:43:11.540
who was really dissociating,

01:43:11.540 --> 01:43:13.670
who could tell us literally
as it was happening.

01:43:13.670 --> 01:43:17.000
And we could see this
pattern, the same pattern

01:43:17.000 --> 01:43:19.430
that was happening in the
mice, in the same patch

01:43:19.430 --> 01:43:22.010
of the brain, we could see that happening

01:43:22.010 --> 01:43:23.960
in the human being at
exactly the right time,

01:43:23.960 --> 01:43:26.350
in the same patch of the
brain that's homologous

01:43:26.350 --> 01:43:29.630
across these immense
evolutionary distances.

01:43:29.630 --> 01:43:32.010
And we knew that it mattered
to both the mouse and human

01:43:32.010 --> 01:43:34.796
because in the human we
could cause it to happen.

01:43:34.796 --> 01:43:36.546
- I just want to underscore the power

01:43:39.554 --> 01:43:42.000
of optogenetics and the ability

01:43:42.000 --> 01:43:46.010
to not just remove a particular
experience or behavior

01:43:46.010 --> 01:43:48.950
by lesioning or destroying,
but then to go back

01:43:48.950 --> 01:43:52.750
and actually activate same
structure or group of structures

01:43:52.750 --> 01:43:54.140
and see the emergences.

01:43:54.140 --> 01:43:56.650
So essentially, these days you hear a lot

01:43:56.650 --> 01:43:57.960
about gain of function research

01:43:57.960 --> 01:43:59.590
in the context of viral manipulation,

01:43:59.590 --> 01:44:00.473
but gain of function is something

01:44:00.473 --> 01:44:01.990
that we do in the laboratory

01:44:01.990 --> 01:44:06.230
and you do in patients, to
both take away something

01:44:06.230 --> 01:44:09.160
and put it back, which
gives you causality.

01:44:09.160 --> 01:44:09.993
- That's right.

01:44:09.993 --> 01:44:11.132
Yeah, and exactly.

01:44:11.132 --> 01:44:14.210
And so with optogenetics,
we were able to provide

01:44:14.210 --> 01:44:18.150
in animals without being
on any ketamine or any drug

01:44:18.150 --> 01:44:19.660
and we could cause the dissociative state

01:44:19.660 --> 01:44:21.900
by playing in a precise
pattern of activity.

01:44:21.900 --> 01:44:23.710
And who would have
thought you could do that?

01:44:23.710 --> 01:44:26.920
But that was a combined
mouse and human paper.

01:44:26.920 --> 01:44:31.920
Likewise, we've been able
to play in visual sensations

01:44:32.200 --> 01:44:37.200
into the brains of mice,
and by observing which cells

01:44:38.310 --> 01:44:40.700
in the visual part of
the brain, visual cortex,

01:44:40.700 --> 01:44:44.610
are naturally responsive to
for example, vertical bars,

01:44:44.610 --> 01:44:47.710
instead of horizontal
bars in the visual world,

01:44:47.710 --> 01:44:50.030
we could see which cells
were normally reporting

01:44:50.030 --> 01:44:52.630
on vertical bars, and then
we could use optogenetics

01:44:52.630 --> 01:44:56.340
to come and play in activity
just to those cells.

01:44:56.340 --> 01:44:58.190
- So these animals are
not viewing anything?

01:44:58.190 --> 01:44:59.380
- Not viewing anything at all.

01:44:59.380 --> 01:45:02.530
And we could activate just
the vertical bar cells,

01:45:02.530 --> 01:45:04.160
and not only did the animal act

01:45:04.160 --> 01:45:05.840
as if it was seeing a vertical bar,

01:45:05.840 --> 01:45:07.810
behaviorally, it was trained
to do a particular thing

01:45:07.810 --> 01:45:09.730
if it saw a vertical bar, and it did that,

01:45:09.730 --> 01:45:12.690
just as if it was seeing
something visually.

01:45:12.690 --> 01:45:14.420
But everything in the brain
that we were recording

01:45:14.420 --> 01:45:18.610
to the internal representation
of this external world

01:45:18.610 --> 01:45:19.880
was naturalistic too.

01:45:19.880 --> 01:45:23.160
It looked like the brain
was seeing something visual.

01:45:23.160 --> 01:45:26.240
So that's gain of function too, you know,

01:45:26.240 --> 01:45:30.200
playing in, providing a
complex sensation or percept

01:45:30.200 --> 01:45:31.510
that wasn't there before.

01:45:31.510 --> 01:45:34.510
And we can do that across species.

01:45:34.510 --> 01:45:38.170
So, and of course mice are social,

01:45:38.170 --> 01:45:41.900
and they do amazing acts
of information processing

01:45:44.101 --> 01:45:46.800
and I try not to disparage
our cousins too much.

01:45:46.800 --> 01:45:48.640
- They certainly have helped
the field of neuroscience

01:45:48.640 --> 01:45:50.080
and medicine I should mention,

01:45:50.080 --> 01:45:51.890
and I know that people
have various sensitivities

01:45:51.890 --> 01:45:55.210
about animal research, but the
work that's been carried out

01:45:55.210 --> 01:45:59.897
in mice has been absolutely
vital and instructional

01:45:59.897 --> 01:46:02.802
for treatment of human disease.

01:46:02.802 --> 01:46:04.040
- That's right.

01:46:04.040 --> 01:46:09.020
- Since we talked about
dissociation and dissociative states

01:46:09.020 --> 01:46:11.570
rather and ketamine,
I'd love your thoughts

01:46:11.570 --> 01:46:14.950
on psychedelic medicine.

01:46:14.950 --> 01:46:19.030
You know, I sort of half joke
having grown up in this area

01:46:19.030 --> 01:46:21.250
in Northern California when it
was much more counter-culture

01:46:21.250 --> 01:46:24.620
than it is now, that many of the things

01:46:24.620 --> 01:46:26.123
that we're hearing about now,

01:46:27.870 --> 01:46:30.550
at least from my read
of the history books,

01:46:30.550 --> 01:46:31.710
happened before.

01:46:31.710 --> 01:46:33.610
There was a movement

01:46:33.610 --> 01:46:36.820
aimed at taking the very
same compounds essentially,

01:46:36.820 --> 01:46:37.910
putting them into patients

01:46:37.910 --> 01:46:41.130
or people who were obviously
using them recreationally,

01:46:41.130 --> 01:46:42.750
but putting them into patients,

01:46:42.750 --> 01:46:44.940
and seeing tremendous positive effects,

01:46:44.940 --> 01:46:49.940
but also tremendous examples
of induced psychiatric illness.

01:46:50.680 --> 01:46:52.470
In other words, many
people lost their minds

01:46:52.470 --> 01:46:54.770
as a consequence of
overuse of psychedelics.

01:46:54.770 --> 01:46:57.773
I'll probably lose a few people out there,

01:46:59.160 --> 01:47:03.180
but I do want to talk
about, what is the state

01:47:03.180 --> 01:47:04.340
of these compounds?

01:47:04.340 --> 01:47:06.450
And I realize it's a huge
category of compounds,

01:47:06.450 --> 01:47:09.840
but LSD and psilocybin, as I
understand trigger activation

01:47:09.840 --> 01:47:12.410
of particular serotonin
receptor mechanisms,

01:47:12.410 --> 01:47:15.300
may or may not lead to
more widespread activation

01:47:15.300 --> 01:47:18.350
of the brain that one
wouldn't see otherwise.

01:47:18.350 --> 01:47:19.670
But when you look at the clinical

01:47:19.670 --> 01:47:21.560
and experimental literature,

01:47:21.560 --> 01:47:23.910
what is your sort of top contour sense

01:47:23.910 --> 01:47:26.170
of how effective these
tools are going to be

01:47:26.170 --> 01:47:27.720
for treating depression?

01:47:27.720 --> 01:47:30.370
And then if we have the time,
we could talk about trauma

01:47:30.370 --> 01:47:32.670
and MDMA and some of that work.

01:47:32.670 --> 01:47:36.280
- Well, you're right to
highlight both the opportunity

01:47:37.601 --> 01:47:39.840
and the parallel that is there.

01:47:39.840 --> 01:47:41.810
And of course we want to help patients

01:47:41.810 --> 01:47:45.310
and of course we want to explore anything

01:47:45.310 --> 01:47:47.390
that might be helpful,

01:47:47.390 --> 01:47:50.470
but we want to do it in
a safe and rigorous way.

01:47:50.470 --> 01:47:53.590
But I do think we should
explore these avenues.

01:47:53.590 --> 01:47:57.170
These are agents that alter reality

01:47:57.170 --> 01:48:00.436
and alter the experience
of reality I should say,

01:48:00.436 --> 01:48:02.523
in relatively precise ways.

01:48:02.523 --> 01:48:05.210
They do have problems,
they can be addictive,

01:48:05.210 --> 01:48:08.603
they can cause lasting
change that is not desirable,

01:48:09.948 --> 01:48:12.380
but we have to see these as opportunities.

01:48:12.380 --> 01:48:15.550
We have to first of all,
study in the laboratory,

01:48:15.550 --> 01:48:17.520
and I'm doing this here.

01:48:17.520 --> 01:48:20.320
You know we have [chuckles] big...

01:48:20.320 --> 01:48:23.050
We have safes with many
interesting psychedelics

01:48:23.050 --> 01:48:24.830
that are all very carefully regulated.

01:48:24.830 --> 01:48:27.290
We get inspections from the DEA and so on.

01:48:27.290 --> 01:48:28.512
- If anyone's hoping to find these labs,

01:48:28.512 --> 01:48:29.810
[Karl laughing]
they exist in outer space,

01:48:29.810 --> 01:48:34.280
so you need to be on board
one of the SpaceX missions

01:48:34.280 --> 01:48:35.113
in order to access them.

01:48:35.113 --> 01:48:36.170
So don't try and come find them.

01:48:36.170 --> 01:48:37.720
- No, that's exactly true. Yes.

01:48:40.438 --> 01:48:42.330
And we're doing exactly this.

01:48:42.330 --> 01:48:43.840
We're saying this is an
incredible opportunity.

01:48:43.840 --> 01:48:46.628
If we could understand how

01:48:46.628 --> 01:48:49.130
the perception of reality is altered,

01:48:49.130 --> 01:48:52.080
we could be creating new
kinds of intervention

01:48:52.080 --> 01:48:54.670
that don't have the risks

01:48:54.670 --> 01:48:59.670
and the problems of causing
lasting change or addiction.

01:49:00.250 --> 01:49:05.250
Now, that said, even as
these medications exist now,

01:49:06.220 --> 01:49:09.260
as you know, there's
an impulse to use them

01:49:09.260 --> 01:49:12.760
in very small doses and to use
them as adjunctive treatments

01:49:12.760 --> 01:49:15.160
for the therapy of various kinds.

01:49:15.160 --> 01:49:18.410
And I'm also supportive
of that if done carefully

01:49:18.410 --> 01:49:20.870
and rigorously, of course there's risk,

01:49:20.870 --> 01:49:23.930
but there's risk with many
other kinds of treatments.

01:49:23.930 --> 01:49:28.930
And I'm not sure that the
risks for these medications

01:49:29.190 --> 01:49:31.420
vastly outweigh the risks
that we normally tolerate

01:49:31.420 --> 01:49:32.860
in other branches of medicine.

01:49:32.860 --> 01:49:34.410
- Why would they work?

01:49:34.410 --> 01:49:39.410
I mean, let's say that
indeed their main effect

01:49:41.030 --> 01:49:44.760
is to create more connectivity,

01:49:44.760 --> 01:49:48.270
at least in the moment
between brain areas.

01:49:48.270 --> 01:49:52.216
So the way I think about the two extremes

01:49:52.216 --> 01:49:53.870
of my experience anyways,

01:49:53.870 --> 01:49:57.360
a high degree of stress and
focus for whatever reason,

01:49:57.360 --> 01:49:59.820
is going to create
changes in my visual field

01:49:59.820 --> 01:50:02.240
and changes in the way
that I perceive times,

01:50:02.240 --> 01:50:03.940
so that I'm on a micro-sliced time,

01:50:03.940 --> 01:50:05.770
I might be in a very contracted view

01:50:05.770 --> 01:50:07.350
of whatever my experience is,

01:50:07.350 --> 01:50:11.620
whereas on the opposite
extreme in a dream or in sleep,

01:50:11.620 --> 01:50:13.470
space and time are very fluid,

01:50:13.470 --> 01:50:15.210
and I'm essentially relaxed,

01:50:15.210 --> 01:50:17.020
although it might be a
very interesting dream,

01:50:17.020 --> 01:50:18.630
or it might not be.

01:50:18.630 --> 01:50:21.690
Psychedelics seemed to be a trajectory.

01:50:21.690 --> 01:50:25.390
I'm not too far off from the dream state

01:50:25.390 --> 01:50:29.920
where space and time are
essentially not as rigid.

01:50:29.920 --> 01:50:32.270
And there is this element of synesthesia,

01:50:32.270 --> 01:50:34.660
blending of the senses, you know,

01:50:34.660 --> 01:50:39.660
feeling colors and hearing
light and things of that sort.

01:50:40.660 --> 01:50:42.423
You hear these reports, anyway.

01:50:43.520 --> 01:50:46.570
Why would having that
dream-like experience

01:50:48.000 --> 01:50:51.620
somehow relieve depression, long-term?

01:50:51.620 --> 01:50:54.170
Do we have any idea why that might be?

01:50:54.170 --> 01:50:55.003
- Yeah.

01:50:56.150 --> 01:50:59.520
We have some ideas, and
no deep understanding.

01:50:59.520 --> 01:51:02.130
One way I think about the psychedelics

01:51:02.130 --> 01:51:07.130
is they increase our willingness to...

01:51:07.300 --> 01:51:08.890
They increase the willingness of our brain

01:51:08.890 --> 01:51:13.380
to accept unlikely ways
of constructing the world,

01:51:13.380 --> 01:51:16.450
unlikely hypothesis, as it
were, as to what's going on.

01:51:16.450 --> 01:51:18.670
The brain, in particular
our cortex, I think,

01:51:18.670 --> 01:51:21.860
is a hypothesis generation
and testing machine.

01:51:21.860 --> 01:51:23.870
It's coming up with
models about everything.

01:51:23.870 --> 01:51:26.920
It's got a lot of bits of data coming in,

01:51:26.920 --> 01:51:29.450
and it's making models
and updating the models

01:51:29.450 --> 01:51:32.653
and changing them, theories,
hypothesis for what's going on.

01:51:33.570 --> 01:51:36.050
And some of those never
reach our conscious mind.

01:51:36.050 --> 01:51:38.370
And this is something I
talk about in "Projections"

01:51:38.370 --> 01:51:42.340
in the book quite a bit, is
many of these are filtered out

01:51:42.340 --> 01:51:45.323
before they get to our
conscious mind, and that's good.

01:51:46.260 --> 01:51:47.460
Think how distracted we'd be

01:51:47.460 --> 01:51:50.190
if we were constantly
having to evaluate all these

01:51:50.190 --> 01:51:52.980
hypotheses about what
kinds of shapes or objects

01:51:52.980 --> 01:51:54.860
or processes were out there.

01:51:54.860 --> 01:51:56.480
And so a lot of this is handled

01:51:57.370 --> 01:51:59.070
before it gets to consciousness.

01:51:59.070 --> 01:52:00.800
What the psychedelics seem to do,

01:52:00.800 --> 01:52:05.800
is they change the threshold
for us to become aware

01:52:06.390 --> 01:52:09.560
of these incomplete hypotheses
or wrong hypotheses,

01:52:09.560 --> 01:52:14.180
or concepts that might be
noise but are just wrong,

01:52:14.180 --> 01:52:17.093
and so are never allowed to
get into our conscious mind.

01:52:17.950 --> 01:52:20.960
Now, that's pretty interesting,

01:52:20.960 --> 01:52:23.300
and it goes wrong in
psychiatric disorders.

01:52:23.300 --> 01:52:26.430
I think in schizophrenia
there's some of the times

01:52:26.430 --> 01:52:29.430
the paranoid delusions that people have

01:52:29.430 --> 01:52:33.310
are examples of these poor models

01:52:33.310 --> 01:52:35.150
that escape into the conscious mind

01:52:35.150 --> 01:52:37.440
and become accepted as reality

01:52:37.440 --> 01:52:39.540
and they never should've gotten out there.

01:52:40.380 --> 01:52:43.210
Now, how could something
like this in the right way,

01:52:43.210 --> 01:52:45.410
help with something like depression?

01:52:45.410 --> 01:52:50.000
Patients with depression often are stuck.

01:52:50.000 --> 01:52:55.000
They can't look into the
future world of possibilities

01:52:57.580 --> 01:52:59.780
as effectively.

01:52:59.780 --> 01:53:03.650
Everything seems hopeless.

01:53:03.650 --> 01:53:05.313
And what does that really mean?

01:53:05.313 --> 01:53:08.350
They discount the value
of their own action,

01:53:08.350 --> 01:53:10.810
they discount the value of the world

01:53:10.810 --> 01:53:13.350
at giving rise to a future that matters.

01:53:13.350 --> 01:53:15.510
Everything seems to run out like a river

01:53:15.510 --> 01:53:17.760
just running out into
a desert and drying up,

01:53:20.090 --> 01:53:22.440
and what these agents may do

01:53:22.440 --> 01:53:25.510
that increase the flow through
circuitry, if you will,

01:53:25.510 --> 01:53:27.480
the percolation of
activity through circuitry

01:53:27.480 --> 01:53:29.340
may end up doing for depression

01:53:29.340 --> 01:53:32.906
is increasing the escape of some tendrils

01:53:32.906 --> 01:53:37.906
of process of forward
progression through the world.

01:53:38.930 --> 01:53:41.690
That's a concept, that's
how I think about it.

01:53:41.690 --> 01:53:43.482
There are ways we can make that rigorous.

01:53:43.482 --> 01:53:47.120
We can indeed identify in
the brain by recording,

01:53:47.120 --> 01:53:50.800
we can see cells that
represent steps along a path

01:53:50.800 --> 01:53:54.200
and look into the future,

01:53:54.200 --> 01:53:56.560
and we can rigorously define these cells

01:53:56.560 --> 01:53:59.310
and we can see if these are
altered on psychedelics.

01:53:59.310 --> 01:54:00.540
And so that's one of the reasons

01:54:00.540 --> 01:54:04.080
that we're working with these
agents in the laboratory

01:54:04.080 --> 01:54:05.920
to say, all right, is
this really the case?

01:54:05.920 --> 01:54:08.419
Are these opening up new paths

01:54:08.419 --> 01:54:11.963
or representations of
paths into the future?

01:54:13.820 --> 01:54:17.460
- MDMA, ecstasy is a unique compound

01:54:17.460 --> 01:54:19.920
in that it leads to big increases

01:54:19.920 --> 01:54:24.720
in brain levels of dopamine
and serotonin simultaneously.

01:54:24.720 --> 01:54:26.770
And I realized that the neuromodulators

01:54:26.770 --> 01:54:29.380
like dopamine and serotonin
often work in concert,

01:54:29.380 --> 01:54:31.630
not alone, the way
they're commonly described

01:54:31.630 --> 01:54:35.490
in the more general popular discussions.

01:54:35.490 --> 01:54:38.920
However, it is a unique compound,

01:54:38.920 --> 01:54:41.100
and it's different than
the serotonergic compounds,

01:54:41.100 --> 01:54:43.470
like LSD and psilocybin.

01:54:43.470 --> 01:54:47.350
And there are now data,

01:54:47.350 --> 01:54:49.780
still emerging that it might be,

01:54:49.780 --> 01:54:54.080
and in some cases can be useful
for the treatment of trauma,

01:54:54.080 --> 01:54:55.963
PTSD and similar things.

01:54:57.896 --> 01:54:59.202
Why would that work?

01:54:59.202 --> 01:55:03.330
And a larger question, perhaps
the more important question

01:55:03.330 --> 01:55:07.823
is, psychedelics, MDMA,
LSD, all those compounds,

01:55:07.823 --> 01:55:10.140
in my mind there are two components.

01:55:10.140 --> 01:55:12.820
There's the experience you
have while you're on them,

01:55:12.820 --> 01:55:15.253
and then there's the
effect they have after.

01:55:16.370 --> 01:55:18.920
People are generating
variations of these compounds

01:55:18.920 --> 01:55:22.020
that are non-hallucinatory variations.

01:55:22.020 --> 01:55:24.700
But, how crucial do you think it is

01:55:24.700 --> 01:55:26.990
to have, let's stay with MDMA,

01:55:26.990 --> 01:55:31.530
the experience of huge levels of dopamine,

01:55:31.530 --> 01:55:33.500
huge levels of serotonin,

01:55:33.500 --> 01:55:35.810
atypical levels of dopamine
and serotonin released,

01:55:35.810 --> 01:55:38.030
having this highly abnormal experience

01:55:38.030 --> 01:55:39.670
in order to be normal again?

01:55:39.670 --> 01:55:40.890
- Yeah.

01:55:40.890 --> 01:55:43.102
I think the brain learns
from those experiences.

01:55:43.102 --> 01:55:46.040
That's the way I see
it, and so for example,

01:55:46.040 --> 01:55:48.013
people who have taken MDMA,

01:55:49.240 --> 01:55:51.720
as you say, there will be the acute phase

01:55:51.720 --> 01:55:54.320
of being on the drug

01:55:54.320 --> 01:55:57.740
and experiencing this
extreme connectedness

01:55:57.740 --> 01:55:59.450
with other people for example,

01:55:59.450 --> 01:56:02.973
and then the drug wears off,

01:56:04.070 --> 01:56:06.160
but the brain learned
from that experience.

01:56:06.160 --> 01:56:09.250
And so what people will report is,

01:56:09.250 --> 01:56:12.680
yeah, I'm not in that state,
but I saw what was possible.

01:56:12.680 --> 01:56:13.593
I saw it. Yeah.

01:56:15.740 --> 01:56:17.520
There don't need to be barriers,

01:56:17.520 --> 01:56:19.810
or at least not as many
barriers as I thought.

01:56:19.810 --> 01:56:21.500
I can connect with more people

01:56:22.929 --> 01:56:24.010
in a way that that is helpful.

01:56:24.010 --> 01:56:27.860
And so I think it's the learning
that happens in that state,

01:56:27.860 --> 01:56:29.550
that actually matters.

01:56:29.550 --> 01:56:30.870
- And as you described that,

01:56:30.870 --> 01:56:32.550
that sounds a lot like what I understand

01:56:32.550 --> 01:56:35.310
to be the hallmark feature of
really good psychoanalysis,

01:56:35.310 --> 01:56:38.650
that the relationship between
patient and therapist,

01:56:38.650 --> 01:56:40.210
hopefully evolves to the point

01:56:40.210 --> 01:56:43.860
where these kinds of tests can be run

01:56:43.860 --> 01:56:45.860
within the context of that relationship,

01:56:45.860 --> 01:56:48.210
and then exported to other relations.

01:56:48.210 --> 01:56:49.250
- Exactly right. Yeah.

01:56:49.250 --> 01:56:51.330
- And that probably, I'm assuming

01:56:51.330 --> 01:56:53.880
is still the goal of really
good psychiatry also.

01:56:53.880 --> 01:56:55.190
- As a part of-

01:56:55.190 --> 01:56:56.730
- Intimacy, really.

01:56:56.730 --> 01:56:58.260
- It should be.

01:56:58.260 --> 01:57:01.700
When we have time, I think
all good psychiatrists

01:57:01.700 --> 01:57:05.650
try to achieve that level
of connection and learning,

01:57:05.650 --> 01:57:10.650
try to help patients create
a new model that is stable,

01:57:11.310 --> 01:57:16.190
that is learned, and that can
help instruct future behavior.

01:57:16.190 --> 01:57:19.640
- One of the things that I
took from reading your book,

01:57:19.640 --> 01:57:22.170
in addition to learning so much science

01:57:22.170 --> 01:57:25.103
and the future of psychiatry
and brain science was,

01:57:28.920 --> 01:57:31.560
amidst this very tragic cases and sadness,

01:57:31.560 --> 01:57:35.240
and a lot of the weight that
